entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Sister Mary had a pleasant day dining with Mr. and Mrs. Greenleaf, with Dr. and Mrs. Sanford also present, and Mrs. Sargent called.

entries.fullText:
brother in law Aaron
M. McLean rounded
out his 81st year
& started into his 82nd!!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's brother-in-law, Aaron M. McLean, turned 81 years old and started his 82nd year.

entries.fullText: at home - & Mrs Greenleaf over - again - In the P.M. Mrs Martha N. Almy - the Vice Pres at Large of the State W.S.A. from Jamestown -arrived - at once - she showed ability to take hold & understand the great work of mapping out the conventions of the sixty counties of the State - which gave me great heart = & hope -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Martha N. Almy, the Vice Pres at Large of the State W.S.A. from Jamestown, arrived and showed ability to take hold & understand the great work of mapping out the conventions of the sixty counties of the State.

entries.fullText: 39th Annual Meeting - County School Commissioners & Superintendents - New Osborn House Hall - 10 O clock - Mrs Almy went over to this meeting and learned that tomorrow would be the time for Mrs Greenleaf to call on the County School Commissioners to record themselves on the woman suffrage amendment -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Almy went over to the 39th Annual Meeting of County School Commissioners & Superintendents at New Osborn House Hall and learned that tomorrow would be the time for Mrs Greenleaf to call on the County School Commissioners to record themselves on the woman suffrage amendment.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Greenleaf
visited the School
Commissioners meeting
and they tabled
her resolution - by
a large majority on
the plea that their's
was not a womans
rights convention!!
entries.summaryText: Mrs Greenleaf visited the School Commissioners meeting and they tabled her resolution.

entries.fullText:
Sister Mary, self
& Mrs Almy also Mrs
Sanford dined
with Mrs Greenleaf
to meet the Cattaraugus
County School Commissioner -
Miss Van Rensselaer
of Randolph - Catt; Co
She is a very bright
woman -
entries.summaryText: Sister Mary, self & Mrs Almy also Mrs Sanford dined with Mrs Greenleaf to meet the Cattaraugus County School Commissioner - Miss Van Rensselaer of Randolph - Catt; Co. She is a very bright woman.

entries.fullText:
All these day
Mrs Almy & self
have been working
out the plan of
Conventions -
, the arranging of
Miss Mary G. Hay
of Indianapolis arrival
this day - & [?] - to
help in the campaign
- all are delighted with
her brightness - she is
very like Anna Shaw
in her quickness of
perception -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about working on the plan of Conventions with Mrs. Almy and the arrival of Miss Mary G. Hay from Indianapolis to help in the campaign. She compares Hay's quickness of perception to Anna Shaw.

entries.fullText:
I went to Church -
Sister Mary remained
at home to work - she
is overwhelmed with
the many, many
kinds of things to do
and ways to them
Mrs Hay went to 1st
Presbyterian - Rev Millard -
& the Mrs Almy went with to
Marcenas Briggs - &
family
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about going to church while Sister Mary stayed home to work. Mrs. Hay went to 1st Presbyterian with Rev Millard and Mrs. Almy went to Marcenas Briggs' house with them.

entries.fullText:
Grand Rally - on the
Con. Con. Woman Suffrage
amendment - City Hall
this evening 8 October - a splendid
audience - Judge Danforth
Presided - Eugene T. Curtis
one of the Resolution Com -
read Judge Raines letter -
Mr. Maine - Ed. Dem & Chron
Chair: Com. on Resolutions -
- Prof. Latimore - the 78th
year - Dr E.M. Moore - on
the platform - the
speaking all good - &
the meeting every way a
success - Our Suffrage
Flag - hung over the stage
with its Colorado Star -
added to its hitherto lone
Star Wyoming -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a Grand Rally on the Con. Con. Woman Suffrage amendment at City Hall in Rochester & Monroe County. The meeting was a success and the Suffrage Flag was hung over the stage.

entries.fullText:
Eugene Mosher - the husband
of our dear Sister Hannah died
this evening at Friend's Hospital -
at Frankford - near Philadelphia -
after being there some three
years - in a demented
state - hardly knowing
his own daughter Louise
who often visited him - It
is good that the spirit has
taken it's flight wholly - from
that wreck of a body -
Took 9 A.M. train for
Syracuse - met Sophie
[G???] - & Mrs Eliz Smith Miller
at Station - & went to home
of Mrs Charles B. Sedgwick
De Witt St - Spoke for the P.E.
Club at 4. and attended a
splendid reception given by
Mrs A. S. Janney - everything
very nice - the best people came
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's sister's husband, Eugene Mosher, passed away at Friend's Hospital in Frankford near Philadelphia. Susan took a train to Syracuse and attended a reception given by Mrs. A. S. Janney.

entries.fullText:
Left Syracuse at at 12:20 - stopped
at home an hour - found a
telegram from niece Louise Mosher
saying "father died last night" -
Miss Mary G. Hay
of Indianapolis went
to Batavia to see about
Hall &c to day - & got
the price of Hall cut down
from $40. to $10 -
The Buffalo & Erie County
Grand Rally this even.
Mrs Greenleaf stopped with
Mr & Mrs Tiffany & I with
Dr Morris - a good -
audience - meeting in its
all - marred only by the
persistence of Mrs Augusta Armstrong
thrusting herself into the niche of
Chairman - which she was wholly
incompetent to fill -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her travels from Syracuse to Batavia and Buffalo, including attending a rally and dealing with the incompetence of a chairman.

entries.fullText:
Miss Wooden of
Indianapolis arrived
to day - She will go through
the County seat towns
& arrange for meetings
Mrs G. & self devoted the
forenoon to helping the
women to organize an
Erie County Campaign
Committee - they elected Mrs
Hawthorne of Eden -

When we reached
home at 5.30 - it was
a blinding snow storm
- Four & Mr G. awaited
us - I took a cab home
- found all going on
well - Miss Annie R. Davis -
[?] Taft Franckin - arrived
to talk this W.C.T.U.
petition interference -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Miss Wooden's arrival and organizing a committee in Erie County, as well as discussing a W.C.T.U. petition interference.

entries.fullText:
Worked all the day trying
to sound out everything in lieu
of letters - wrote darling niece
Louise - H. Mosher James
of Phila. who has had the
sad ordeal of looking after
the last service to her father
who died Tuesday night the 9th
at Orthodox Friends Hospital
at Frankford - near Phila -
It was cruel that neither
sister Mary nor self could
possibly go to her - without -
stopping the wheels of many
other's work [& the].
Mrs Davis, Mrs Almy, Mrs G.
& self - talked & talked & all
agreed the W.C.T.U. petition
a great hindrance - if not an
utter defeat - of our Millions
Petition - she left at 9.20 - &
I took the 10.25 train - which was
2 hours late - & because of it - my
trunk made station & my [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her day, including writing to her niece, H. Mosher James, who has had a sad ordeal, and discussing the hindrance of the W.C.T.U. petition.

entries.fullText:
Lecture this evening for the
Michigan State University Lecture
Association of Ann Arbor -
Wm. W. Wedemeyer - Pres -
- first woman since war
times when Anna E.
Dickinson - was thus honored
- Gave my Power of the ballot
to bring equal chances in the
world of work & wages
Arrived two hours late
guest of dear Mrs Israel
Hale - Mrs Stanton's thirty-,
year housekeeper - Amelia
Willard - now 70 - & more
came over from Ypsilanti to
see me - & I must go to bed
& sleep & be rested for the evening's
work - so the poor woman
had to go back without my
answering her many questions about
the children & Mrs Stanton
A fine audience in the
3000 capacity University Hall -
[?] 1,500 - a lovely evening - &
Mrs Hall & daughters Louise & Charlotte
said I made good speech
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony gives a lecture at the Michigan State University Lecture Association of Ann Arbor and stays with Mrs Israel Hale. She also meets with Amelia Willard and has a successful speech.

entries.fullText:
-
At Ann Arbor
guest of my dear, dear
friend Mrs Olivia Bigelow
Hall -

Gave a lecture before
the University Christian
Association at 9 Oclock
this A.M. on
"Moral influence versus
Political power" - to a
fine audience in
Newbury Hall - their
own building -

Staid in house all
the P.M. & eve'g,
as a result didn't
sleep so well - I must
have out of door exercise
& air to sleep well -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony gave a lecture before the University Christian Association at 9 O'clock this A.M. on "Moral influence versus Political power" to a fine audience in Newbury Hall. She stayed in the house all the P.M. & eve'g, as a result didn't sleep so well - I must have out of door exercise & air to sleep well -

entries.fullText:
Ann Arbor -
weather warm foggy
& raining -
entries.summaryText: The weather in Ann Arbor was warm, foggy, and raining.

entries.fullText:
Left Ann Arbor - at 11 -
arrived - Toledo about 1. P.M.
Connie Mott - Mrs Hall - &
self - we went to Miss Motts
& had a quiet afternoon
I taking a good sleep -
Mrs Sarah Williams &
daughter called in
the eve'g -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Ann Arbor and arrived in Toledo where she spent a quiet afternoon with Connie Mott and Mrs. Hall. Mrs. Sarah Williams and her daughter visited in the evening.

entries.fullText:
At Toledo - with
Miss Anna C. Mott - the
only child of Richard Mott -
to celebrate the 25th
anniversary of the W.S.A.
of the [?] - formed by Mrs
Stanton & self the 9th of
March 1869!! at Mrs Halls home
Splendid & large reception
at Church of our Father Parlor
in the P.M. 2. to 5 - and
packed church in the
evening - The 21 years report
of work done was splendid
Mrs Segur President,
Mrs Bissell, Mrs [?] et al
there -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a celebration in Toledo with Miss Anna C. Mott to commemorate the 25th anniversary of the W.S.A. formed by Mrs. Stanton and herself. The event included a reception and a packed church in the evening where a report of the 21 years of work was presented. Mrs. Segur and Mrs. Bissell were among those present.

entries.fullText:
Took trains - at 7:40. A.M.
at Waggon Works - on Mich.
Central - dozed all day - without
fairly noticing the places
we rolled by until the Porter
sang out - Niagara Falls on
the right side - the Majest
waters pour over as ever -
at 8:20 we rolled into
the Rochester Station -
found Sister Mary - as
overwhelmed with the
Campaign Mountain
as ever - no not quite
so much -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels by train from Waggon Works to Rochester Station, passing by Niagara Falls, and meets with Sister Mary.

entries.fullText:
At Home -
Sister Mary & self - & Mrs
Almy heard Jenkins
Lloyd Jones of Chicago
Preach for Mr Gannett -
on - They have taken
Our Lord away - & we
know not where they
have laid him" - It
was a splendid sermon
- Mr Gannet asked
me home to dinner
with them - Mrs Blackall
& Mrs Kittridge there also -
- Called at the
Greenleafs [after] Miss Mills
niece - learned that
Auntie Cook died yesterday
A.M. was found dead in
her bed - so called at the
house of Mrs Eliza J. Clapp who
willed me $1000 - which is
not yet paid me - Mr
Geo. Samens is executor -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a sermon by Jenkins Lloyd Jones, has dinner with Mr Gannet and others, and learns of the death of Auntie Cook and a $1000 inheritance from Mrs Eliza J. Clapp.

entries.fullText:
Left Rochester at 10.20 for
Albion - to attend the
first - Orleans County -
of our sweep of 60 -
County Mass Meetings
Mrs Spencer met us -
& took me to the
school Sup't - Prof
Green - whose wife
is a grand- daughter
of Austin Cross - & daughter
of Farrington Price -
Had a packed Court
House in evening - & a
good audience in P.M.
Miss Hay's managed
nicely - good men &
women came from every
township -
entries.summaryText: Attended the first Orleans County Mass Meetings in Albion, met with Mrs Spencer and Prof Green, and had a packed Court House in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Genessee County -
Batavia - Free Will
Baptist Church - in afternoon -
& The Opera House - evening -
guest of Mrs Dr Tozier -
- Left Albion. 8.40 - reach
Rochester 9.45 - Lunched at
home - took train at 2.25 -
for Batavia - went to church
found 200 - best men & women
there - & Harriet May Mills
managing things finely -
Evening brought a packed
house & many left - because
of not finding even standing room
- made my Bread & Ballot
speech here - Brain
got fairly alive - so sleep
never came till almost
morning -
entries.summaryText: Attended the Free Will Baptist Church and The Opera House in Batavia, had lunch at home in Rochester, and gave a speech on Bread & Ballot.

entries.fullText:
Left Batavia at 8.33 -.
reached Warsaw - 10 - dined
with Mrs Crossett - rain
& snow came - found a
fair audience at 2.20 -
Miss Hay managed well
made short talk - there in a
driving snow storm - went to Mrs
Humphreys - & to bed - was
so sleepy -- got up rested - &
found M.E. Church well
filled - spite of the storm -
- Mr Hayden Humphrey
presided - made splendid
speech in introducing me - & he
said - after we got home - You
made just the right speech
for this audience - Miss
Hay stopped at Mrs Hs also
- & little Maude H. was
jubilant in her welcome
[?] Aunt Susan -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Warsaw, gives a speech at the Methodist Church, and stays at Mrs. Humphrey's house.

entries.fullText:
Left Warsaw - 7.25 - reached
R. 9. - stopped till 11.50 - reached
Pen Zan - 1.50 found Mrs
Julia Sheppard - (John) at
station - who took both Miss Mills
& self to there palatial home -
- small meeting - 100 - in P.M.
- Pretty chilly house - but -
spoke & then rushed back to
Mrs Sheppards & went to bed -
- but sleep hardly came -
- had - 200 - or more at
evening meeting - Judge Strauss
Presided & made good speech
- Rev. Copeland - M.E. Pastor
Prayed - - The Pastors - & 20
so called business men, sent
Protest to head-quarters - against
our coming to Pen-Zan now
however they were holding a revival
meeting - all the churches [?] them
& they were giving their meeting this evg -
also the Yates Co. Teachers institute
was in session -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Pen Zan, gives speeches at Sheppard's Opera House, and faces opposition from local pastors and business men.

entries.fullText:
Decided to remain over &
go through with this Jates Co.
meeting - & see & hear Mrs Howell -
- & hold the Fort to the
end of our meeting - to the
best of our ability = the
Ministers have made a special
women's serial meet'g this
afternoon - it looks very
like old times - to keep
the women away from our
meet'g -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony decides to stay for a meeting and mentions Mrs. Howell and the Ministers making a special women's serial meeting to keep women away from their meeting.

entries.fullText:
Fessinger Hall -
Seneca Co. - Waterloo -
Mrs Harriet [?]
Miss May Hunt -
daughter of Richard
& Sarah Hunt - was at
the meeting = the day
& evening were a fearful
wind & snow storm
very few at meeting
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a meeting held at Fessinger Hall in Waterloo, Seneca Co. on January 30, 1894. She mentions that Mrs Harriet and Miss May Hunt, daughter of Richard and Sarah Hunt, were present at the meeting. The day and evening were affected by a wind and snow storm, and very few people attended the meeting.

entries.fullText:
Fitzhugh Hall - Rev Olm B. Coit -
Mrs E.S. Coit - 60 East 4th st -
M.E. minister - had Presiding Elder
Shepherd & wife - & Mr Coon & wife to
tea - all opposed, to W.S. save
dear Mrs Coit herself - & she was
a school mate of dear Rachel
Foster in Philadelphia - her name
was Emma Stitzer - she
is very bright & earnest -
The Hall was packed & I just
showed how contemptible
Ministers as a class are with
Legislatures - because they only
represent voteless women - &
ditto teachers & c
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a meeting held at Fitzhugh Hall in Oswego, Oswego Co. on January 31, 1894. She mentions that Rev Olm B. Coit, Mrs E.S. Coit, Presiding Elder Shepherd and wife, and Mr Coon and wife were present at the meeting. She also mentions Emma Stitzer, who was a schoolmate of Rachel Foster in Philadelphia. The Hall was packed, and Susan B. Anthony expressed her opinion on how contemptible ministers and teachers are with legislatures because they only represent voteless women.

entries.fullText:
1st Day of Richmond Co. Dunn County
Port Richmond -
Castleton Hall - in
Hotel - Miss Shaws
night beggarly audience -
& mine the second not
much better - Miss
Hay's courage is
marvelous - big
hall rent - & big
Hotel bills for all of
Mrs Geo. Wm. Curtis came
my night -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her experience on the first day of Richmond Co. Dunn County, including the poor audience turnout, high expenses, and the presence of Miss Shaws, Miss Hay, and Mrs Geo. Wm. Curtis.

entries.fullText:

White Plains - Stopped at
private House - Meeting in
public hall - very fair -
Mary Seymour Howell prayer
Miss Shaw first night & I
the second -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her experience on the first day of Westchester Co., including staying at a private house, a meeting in a public hall, and the presence of Mary Seymour Howell and Miss Shaw.

1st Day - Queens Co. Mass Meeting.
Jamaica - Town Hall -
2d [?] of Westchester - take - 2.09. [?]
Carrie Chapman Catt - Manger
Guests of Mr & Mrs -
- lovely people -
Miss Shaw spoke first

entries.summaryText: Attended Queens Co. Mass Meeting in Jamaica. Carrie Chapman Catt was the manager. Miss Shaw spoke first and Anthony spoke in the evening.

entries.fullText:
1st Day - Suffolk County -
Riverhead - Opera
House -
May G. H. Manager -
guests of Mrs --
- good people -
Shaw First eve'g -
Anthony - the second
entries.summaryText: Attended a meeting in Suffolk County at the Riverhead Opera House. May G. H. was the manager. Shaw spoke first and Anthony spoke in the evening.

entries.fullText:
2d Day Riverhead - Suffolk Co.
18th County Mass Meeting -
The old skating rink - for evenings
& The old Court House for P.M. meetings
Miss Hay's - manager -
guest of Mr & Mrs
Frances McCabe-Rogers - Mrs
R. the niece of Eliza & Wag. McCabe
& daughter of John McCabe of Palatine
Bridge - Eliza McCabe used to be my
dress maker in 1846.7.8.&9 - When
I was principal of girls department of
the Old Canajoharie Academy - in
1847-8.9. - had largest audience of
the whole 18 - mass meetings - made
my bread & ballot speech -
entries.summaryText: Attended the 18th County Mass Meeting in Riverhead, Suffolk Co. and stayed with Miss Hay's. Met with Mr & Mrs Frances McCabe-Rogers and Eliza McCabe, who used to be her dress maker. Gave a speech on bread and ballot.

entries.fullText:
Left Riverhead in P.M.
Spent night with Cousin
S. V. Lapham - Miss
Hay remained over
Sunday - won't travel
on Sunday -
entries.summaryText: Left Riverhead and spent the night with Cousin S. V. Lapham. Miss Hay remained in Riverhead as she does not travel on Sundays.

entries.fullText:
Putnam - 21st County Mass Meeting
Wea. Mon. March 5, 1894 Ther.
Putnam Co. Brewster's -
Take 10:30 - train - Anna Shaw
& self managers of Put - meetings -
Both of us here - this
eve'g - and Miss Shaw
at Carmel - both
lean & lank everyway -
entries.summaryText: Attended 21st County Mass Meeting in Putnam with Anna Shaw.

Wea. Tues. March 6, 1894 Ther.
2d day Putnam Co. - Carmel -
1st day - Duchess Co. Mass meeting -
at Poughkeepsie. Miss Hay manager
Old M. Church - Cannon St -
Guest of Mrs Julia P. Meeks -
20 - Garfield Place - over 86 years of age
Mrs G. R. Brown - the Pres. of
W.C.T.U. very helpful -
Anthony spoke first
night = & before leaving on
Wednesday - called at Vassar
to try to get Pres. Taylor to
invite Miss Shaw to talk
to the girls - but it
was impossible - he said -
entries.summaryText: Attended 21st County Mass Meeting in Duchess and Poughkeepsie, stayed with Mrs. Julia P. Meeks and met with Mrs. G. R. Brown. Tried to get Miss Shaw to speak at Vassar but was unsuccessful.

good audience

Harriet May Mills - Manager -
Mrs Sarah A. Kenny -
Harmony Hall - Stopped

- Just after the
murder of Ross - on
city election day - great
excitement over that -
but next to no interest
in our meeting -
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on March 8, 1894 about a mass meeting in Hudson and a lack of interest in their meeting due to the recent murder of Ross on city election day.

good audience
entries.summaryText: Attended a church service in Schenectady and was a guest of Rev & Mrs. Sewall.

entries.fullText:
2d day Schenectady Co -
Left at 8 A.M. for
home - Miss
Shaw spoke this evening -
entries.summaryText: Left Schenectady and returned home. Miss Shaw spoke in the evening.

entries.fullText:
went to House of Refuge at 2 P.M. -
Mrs Greenleaf came
over -

Pop of Albany County is 164,555 - The Vote - 32,911 -
entries.summaryText: Visited House of Refuge and met with Mrs Greenleaf. Recorded population and vote count of Albany County.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Albany Co. -25th Con.
Albany - Young Mens Hall -
Kate Stoneman & Mrs G.R. Hitt
136 - State Street -
[Had the Assembly
Chamber packed -
Mrs Howell president
Rec. Ecoh prayed] -
and Miss Shaw spoke
in Albany this evening -
and I had plain black
satin fitted - Mrs Fullam
too ill to do it - her first
girl - tried her hand -
entries.summaryText: Attended the first day of the Albany County 25th Convention at Young Mens Hall. Recorded various events and people encountered throughout the day.

entries.fullText:
Pop. 31, 598 - The vote - 6,315 -
Wea. TUES. MARCH 13, 1894 Ther.
26th - Con,
Green County - Catskill - the 26th
Mrs Stephen Root -
Liberty St - hall [?]
Local manager - Mrs G.N. Brandow
=
2d day of the Albany 25th [?]
Left Rochester at 8.29 - reached
Albany at 2. P.M - took lunch
on train - So went strat to
bed - & at evening had the
assembly chamber packed -
Rev Ecoh prayed - Mrs
Howell spoke first & took
up the collection - and at
close of the meeting the
Albany Educational & Industrial
Union gave me a reception
in the Assembly Parlor -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Albany and attends a meeting where Mrs. Howell speaks first and takes up the collection. At the close of the meeting, the Albany Educational & Industrial Union gave her a reception in the Assembly Parlor.

entries.fullText:
Pop. of Orange County - 97,859 - the vote - 19,572
Wea. Wed. March 14, 1894 Ther.
1st day - Orange the 27th Co - Newburg -
Opera House -
Miss Clara Taft - Hostess for
Miss Shaw - Mrs Howell & self -
Miss Shaw manager the P.M. meeting -
for Mrs H & spoke this evening
while I spoke at Cattskill
& was guest of Mr. and Mrs.
Stephen Root -
3d evening in Albany - Mrs
Howell - the speaker -
she says a perfect
oration to her !
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting in Newburg and speaks at Cattskill while being a guest of Mr. and Mrs. Stephen Root. Mrs. Howell speaks in Albany and says it was a perfect oration to her.

entries.fullText:
1st day Ulster Co - Kingston -
Anna Shaw spoke - Court House
M.G. Hay - manager - Miss Shaw
guest of Lucy E's Uncle - Henry B. Luther
2d - of Orange - left Cattskill at 9:40 -
reached Newburg at - 1. P.M.
Miss Shaw & Miss Clara Taft at station
2d day of Orange Co. meeting -
- Opera house well packed
Mrs Howell arrived same time &
reported splendid meeting in Albany
last evening - Miss Shaw
went on to Rockland -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a meeting in Kingston, Ulster Co. where Anna Shaw spoke at the Court House. They then went to Orange Co. where they attended a meeting at the Opera House. Mrs. Howell reported a splendid meeting in Albany.

entries.fullText:
1st day Rockland County -
mass meeting - Haverstraw -
Opera House - Miss Mills -
manager - Miss Shaw spoke this
evening - both stopped at Mr &
Mrs Harvey Johnson - Mrs Ruth
Johnson -
2d day of Ulster Co.
Left Newburg at 9.20 & reached
Kingston at 10:20 - found Miss
Shaw at cousin H.B. Luther's
- learned that hundreds couldn't
get into the C.H. last night - and
ordered the Opera House to
engaged - & it was packed
in the evening - and a $50 -
collection that paid for it
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a mass meeting in Haverstraw, Rockland County where Miss Shaw spoke at the Opera House. They then went back to Ulster Co. where they found out that hundreds couldn't get into the Court House the previous night and ordered the Opera House to be engaged.

entries.fullText:
2d Day of Rockland Co -
Haverstraw - Opera House -
Miss Mills manager -
Left Kingston at 11.50 - &
reached Haversham at 1.40 -
guest of Mr & Mrs
Frank Felter - near
the west shore station -
- had a good sleep - &
found [?] letters - among
them on from Rachel - saying
her resignation had been awful
& Mrs Richards elected - wants
my sanction - after it is all
done!! So I gave it - though
not altogether cheerfully -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Haverstraw and stayed with Mr. and Mrs. Frank Felter. She received a letter from Rachel about her resignation and gave her sanction.

entries.fullText:
In Haverstraw
at the Felters
spoke in Opera House
at 3 P.M. to a
large audience -
Miss Mills took
the collection -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spoke at the Opera House in Haverstraw to a large audience and Miss Mills took the collection.

entries.fullText:
1st Day - Sullivan Co. the 29th Mass Meeting -
Liberty - Music Hall -
guest of Miss Darbee - Miss
Shaw with me - and I
made a mighty poor
speech - left thinking
how much better she
could do -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a mass meeting in Sullivan Co. and gives a poor speech.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Chenango County -
Norwich - Y.M.C.A. Hall
Miss Mills manager -
Left Oneonta at 7.20 - reached
Norwich at 11 - stopped at
Eagle Hotel - Miss Miles
came yesterday - found nothing -
arranged - so had to run
everywhere to get people
waked up to the fact of
our meeting
Miss Shaw spoke
Second evening -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting in Chenango County and Miss Shaw speaks on the second evening.

entries.fullText:
1st - Broome County
Binghampton -
Court House
guest of M.H. Wilkinson
his new wife of 4 years
& daughter Anna - & son
Arthur - Dear cousin Harriet
died ten years ago -
& this is my first visit
since that -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits M.H. Wilkinson and his family in Broome County, Binghampton and Court House. She meets his new wife and daughter Anna and son Arthur. She also mentions her cousin Harriet who died ten years ago.

entries.fullText:
In Binghamton
at W. H. Wilkinsons -
niece Lucy E. came
with Miss Shaw
but did not stay
with the Wilkinsons -
only Lucy E. was at
dinner - before Anna's
arrived
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is in Binghamton at W. H. Wilkinsons. Her niece Lucy E. comes with Miss Shaw but does not stay with the Wilkinsons. Only Lucy E. was at dinner before Anna's arrival.

entries.fullText:
In Binghamton
at cousin Harriet
Richardsons home -
M.H. Wilkinson - married
again - pleasant woman -
- both of cousins
children seem happy with
their fathers new wife -
Anna - 25 years old calls
the wife Aunt Virginia
in a very sweet way Arthur
is in his fathers store or
tannery - Hinckley
Short - son of Aunt
Lucy Shorts son Glover
called - is a strongly marked
Richardson - Samuel
Wadsworth - grand son
of old Uncle Josheph
Wadsworth of Auburn
called also -
Miss Shaw preached &
had packed M.E. Church
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits cousin Harriet Richardson in Binghamton and meets M.H. Wilkinson, who has remarried. She also mentions other family members and a sermon by Miss Shaw at the M.E. Church.

entries.fullText:
1st day Cortland County -
Cortland
Universalist Church
guest of Clara Thompson Yale -
her son - William in first year at
Cornell University -
Church packed to
suffocation - 500 - perhaps -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends the first day in Cortland County and is a guest of Clara Thompson Yale. She also mentions the packed Universalist Church and William, who is in his first year at Cornell University.

entries.fullText:
1st day Tompkins County
Ithica - Library Hall
Guest - Dr Winslow - Cor of
Seneca & Quarry streets -
On reaching Ithica -
- Mr W. was not at home -
- so went to Clinton Hotel -
- & took my P.M. sleep -
after the meeting Mrs Prof -
Jones insisted on taking
me home with her -
had fair audience - though
it is Easter vacation &
nearly all the students
out of the village
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Ithica, Tompkins County and speaks at Library Hall. She stays at the Clinton Hotel and is taken home by Mrs. Prof Jones. She notes that the audience was fair despite it being Easter vacation and most students being out of the village.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Tioga County -
Owego - Court House
Guest of my dear
old Revolution clerk
Elizabeth Brown
Chatfield - 18 North Front St -
- talked over Anna
Dickinson & took a
sleep in P.M -
had court house full
Mrs Howell stopped
with Lib - also -
Mary Bowen Dean -
of South Adams lives
in Owego - & went to
P.M. meeting hoping to see me
her daughter Mrs Clark
spoke to me at evening meeting -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Owego, Tioga County and speaks at the Court House. She stays with Elizabeth Brown and discusses Anna Dickinson. She notes that the court house was full and Mrs. Howell and Mary Bowen Dean also stayed with Lib. Mrs. Clark spoke to her at the evening meeting.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Schuyler County
Watkins - [M.E. Church] Opera House
Mrs C.A. Holden & daughter
Mrs Mary Robbins Mead -
near the station - both Miss
Mills & self stopped with these
very cordial women -
had a good audience
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her first day in Schuyler County, where she stopped with Mrs. C.A. Holden and her daughter, Mrs. Mary Robbins Mead, and Miss Mills. They had a good audience.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Chemung County
Elmira -
Sunday School Room - Baptist
Church - a most humiliating
thing - not to be let into the church
proper -
Guest of Ex. Congressman
& Mrs Rockwell
064 - Clinton Street
She invited to supper the
Rev Tom Beecher & wife - he
is now over 70 - though the
youngest of the old Lyman
Beecher family - Miss Hays
there to tea also - Mrs
Beecher went to Lecture -
no one to introduce me -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her first day in Chemung County, where she was not allowed into the church proper. She was a guest of Ex. Congressman and Mrs. Rockwell and had supper with Rev Tom Beecher and his wife, Miss Hays, and Mrs. Beecher. No one introduced her.

entries.fullText:
Left Elmira at 10:15 -
and reached Rochester at
2. found Sister Mary alone -
That is Mrs Almy gone home -
& Mrs Greenleaf also had left -
- After tea we went over
to Mrs G's - found them in
great sorrow that all
hope of saving their Sons &
Susie Moores - eldest boy - has
gone - so a big cloud
is over the household -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Rochester and spends time with Sister Mary, Mrs. Almy, and Mrs. Greenleaf. She also visits the G family, who are in great sorrow over the loss of their sons and Susie Moores.

entries.fullText:
At home - 17 Madison St -
Rochester N.Y. -
A lovely day marked & wrote
letters & sent a copy to Mrs
Thurston - & Mrs Otis of the
Kansas State Suffrage
Amendment campaign
Committee - giving reasons
why the Peoples & Republican
parties must - put planks in
their platforms - there
is a fearfully weak-kneedness
out there - for the parties
not to do it - is defeat before
we start into the campaign -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends a lovely day at home in Rochester and writes letters to Mrs. Thurston and Mrs. Otis of the Kansas State Suffrage Amendment campaign Committee, urging the Peoples and Republican parties to put planks in their platforms.

entries.cityOrState: Steuben 39th County - Cassino - Bath - Court House
entries.fullText:
1st day - Steuben 39th County -
Cassino
Bath - Court House
Mrs Wm. H. Nichols -
Mr. Nichols is member of
Con. Con. from 27th Senatorial District
- & is earnest on our side -
Miss Mills delighted every
body - in the P.M. -
About 6 oclock there came
from Strauss & Co - Washington
D.C. a great box - by express -
with 74 - American Beaties -
roses - ordered - he said -
to be delivered Feb. 15. at our
Wash. Con. - undoubtedly from
a [?] - dear Mrs S.E. Gross of
Chicago - dear Mrs Nichols
put the huge pile in a great
tin pail - bandaged with cotton
tied with a yellow ribbon - &
placed them on table at my side
while speaking in the Cassino -
to a magnificent audience
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks in Steuben 39th County and receives a box of roses from Mrs. S.E. Gross of Chicago.

entries.cityOrState: Allegany County - in Wellsville - M.E. Church
entries.fullText:
1st day - Allegany County -
in Wellsville - M.E. Church -
Guest of Mr & Mrs Frank B Church -
Mr Church is member of Con. Con.
from the 32d Senatorial District & is
splendidly on our side -
Oscar A Fuller - another member
of the Con. Con. introduced me -
- a splendid audience
of a full 1,000 -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks at the M.E. Church in Wellsville to an audience of 1,000 people.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Cattaraugus Co.
Olean - Hall -
Guest of the Mayor of the city
Mr V.N.N. Franchet -
Corner of Sullivan & Second Streets
arrived 10.30 A.M. found
carriage at Station - raining
like a genuine April day -
This is Olean's first
year as a City - and
Mr Franchet is their
first mayor - they
have five children three
girls & two boys -
Mrs Franchets name is Annie W -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Olean, Cattaraugus Co. and meets with the mayor, Mr. V.N.N. Franchet, and his family.

entries.fullText:
Chautauqua County -
Dunkirk - Miss Hay
Columbus Hall
all guests of Edith
Williams - wife - daughter -
Mrs Scott - Son & grand
children Scott -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Dunkirk, Chautauqua County and stays with Edith Williams and her family.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Erie Co. - Miss Mills
Buffalo - - Concert Hall
Guest of Dr Sarah Morris
159 - Franklin Street -
Ex. Surrogate Judge
Hammond introduced me
to the audience -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a concert in Buffalo and is introduced to the audience by Hammond.

geographicalLocations: Church on East side of the city
entries.fullText:
2d day - Erie [Niagara ] County
Buffalo
Miss Shaw speaks this -
evening at Church on East
side of the city -
I left for home
at noon -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a speech by Miss Shaw in Buffalo before leaving for home at noon.

entries.fullText:
At Home -
Miss Shaw preached
in Delaware St - M.E
Church - Buffalo this evening
- Went to Church -
Mr Gannett - he preached
on the woman element
- good -
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw and Mr. Gannett preached at Delaware St - M.E Church - Buffalo.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Niagara County
Lockport - Miss Mills
Court House in P.M. - and
in ev'g - Music Hall - which
was packed -
[Ex Surrogate Judge
Hammond introduced me]
all were entertained
at the Commercial hotel
- neither Mrs Lurch-
nor Mrs. Sam'l Chushing
were able to be out -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was introduced by Ex Surrogate Judge Hammond at Music Hall in Niagara County Lockport.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Monroe County -
Rochester - Miss [?]
Washington Rink -
Guests - all of us - at No.17 -
Left Lockport at 7.20 A.M. -
- went to bed at usual
after dinner - got a good
rest - took my good
cup of coffee - and
though the snow & rain
& slush & slop were
simply awful - we had
600 or more in the
great barn of a place.
ex M.C. Greenleaf introduced
me - & all declared I made a
a good speech in my
own home city - for
which I was profoundly thankful
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks in Rochester, Monroe County to a crowd of 600 people.

entries.fullText:
1st day Livingston county
Genesee - Mrs Howell manager -
Concert Hall -
Guest of Mrs Alice Arnold Cone -
Left A. at 9.25 - - had
a nice sleep in P.M.
and though the snow
was fully two feet deep -
the hall was packed - &
many had to go away for
lack of room - many
were students of the
normal school
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks in Livingston County to a packed hall of students from the normal school.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Ontario Co. Miss [?]
Canandaigua - M.E. Church
Guest of Miss Comstock -
(slept in her room) and
of Miss Crocker & Miss
- the three women
own Granger Place -
- & have 30 boarders -
in their "Granger School"
with day pupils beside -
Church packed -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Ontario Co. and stays with Miss Comstock and Miss Crocker in Canandaigua.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Onondaga Co.
Syracuse - Miss Mills
Wieting Opera House -
Left C. at - 9.30 - and
was guest of dear Mrs
Hall's sister - Mrs Mary
Bigelow Phillips - at
903 - West Genesee St -
- who is to sail for Europe
April 28 - with her niece
Dear Lou Hall Walker -
- Had lower floor of the
Opera House filled - say
4 or 500 - the weather pleasant
- & no reason why every seat
not filled - but it was
a first class quality - & I
made my most telling speech
as to say we must have
political party endorsement
& of their mechanics &
thinking[?] used to cary
our amendment -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Onondaga Co. and stays with Mrs Mary Bigelow Phillips in Syracuse. She speaks at the Wieting Opera House about the need for political party endorsement for their amendment.

entries.fullText:
Left Mrs Phillips &
Syracuse at 9:30 - and
arrived - Geneva at noon -
to see [th??] dear friends
Mrs Eliz. Smith & Normie
Miller - & Mrs Stanton
who is visiting them - Mr
Miller, too, always -
a telegram came from
Hattie Stanton Blatch & Nora
saying they had arrived at
26 West 61st - New York -
- Mrs Miller & Nan. had
invited a hundred ladies &
gentlemen to a parlor meeting
at 3.30 - so the parlors were
filled & Mrs S. & self talked
to them - Mrs Miller has over
a thousand signatures to the
petition - both mother and
daughter are thoroughly
roused to work for the petition
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits friends in Geneva and attends a parlor meeting in New York to discuss a petition.

entries.fullText:
At Geneva -
with Mrs Eliz Smith and
Charles Dudley Miller -
- Mrs Stanton & self
working away at new
[Cyclopedia] article
for Johnson Cyclopedia
Mrs Brayton & two daughters
called - Mrs B's father
was Rufus Richardson -
brother of cousin Ira
Richardson - here learned
that Cousin Lucius
Home was reduced to
honesty - his wife & daughter are
both very feeble - so that the
well daughter has to devote
her whole time to them
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony works on a new article and receives news about family in Geneva.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Cayuga Co. Miss Mills -
Auburn - Burtis Opera
House - guests of
dear Eliza Wright Osborn -
Found both Miss Shaw
& niece Lucy E. - [?] and
Miss Mills at Mrs Osborns -
- The Opera House was
packed - but I didn't
make as good a speech
here as at Syracuse -
for which lack - I felt
awfully sorry - but it is
of no use to worry - I surely
come more nearly to not making a
total failure - than I did
thirty years ago - I do succeed
in wading through & clutching
at some links - even if I
fail to connect all of them
into a complete chain
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks at Burtis Opera House in Auburn, Cayuga Co. and reflects on her speech.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Madison Co.
[Canastota] Opera House Miss Hay
Oneida - Guest
of Eliza Kerr Col -
Grove Street - and
Mr E. Emmons Col - they
used to live at Peterboro -
so talked of Gerrit Smith -
Had packed audience -
did better - than at Auburn
but my best - their
neighbor Mrs Goodwin
dined with us -
Miss Hay reported that
Mrs Greenleafs boy - Holly was
buried yesterday P.M. - - so
the body is at rest - - &
Miss Hay reported their
Susan - the mother of the
boy very ill - & the fear that
she would go the same way -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks at Canastota Opera House in Madison Co. and Oneida and discusses local news with her hosts.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Herkimer Co
Herkimer
Opera House - Miss Mills -
Palmer Hotel - -
Judge Ezra B Graves
daughter - Mrs. gave
me cordial welcome -
- Hon. & Mrs Warner
Miller live here - but
from stupid blunder
Mr Miller wasn't
specially included - as
he should have been -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Herkimer, is welcomed by Judge Ezra B Graves and Hon. & Mrs Warner Miller.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Oneida Co. Miss Mills
Utica - Music Hall
Guest of Mrs Frances A.
Goodale - 369 - Genessee Street
Large audience -
a splendid reception
& Luncheon - at[?] the
new Century club at
their parlors - this noon-
Cousin Rosette Read
Blue - dear mother's brother
Aaron's daughter, came
in from Clinton - with
her only daughter -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Utica, is a guest of Mrs Frances A. Goodale and attends a reception at the new Century club. Cousin Rosette Read Blue visits from Clinton.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Lewis Co.
Lowville - Miss Hay
M.E. Church -
guest of Mrs Pitcher - Took
tea with Mrs George Fowler -
with I stopped in Dec. 1870 - or
thereabouts - she has been ill
for three years - so cannot work
for the Am't - Mrs
O'Donnell - called - introduced
me - said she drove - as a school
girl from McGrawville College
to Cortland - to see & hear me
in 1854!!
Mrs F.E. Miller - Local manager
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Lewis Co., meets with various people and attends M.E. Church.

entries.fullText:
Left Lowville at. 10.40 - for
Boonville - the old
home of Helen Philleo -
now Mrs Jenkins of Detroit -
Guest of Mrs W.W. Rinkle
- her husband an old school
Doctor - three boys & one girl
- meeting in Comstock Hall -
- 3 or 4 hundred people - it
was Mrs Howell's - place - but
she declined to fill it -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Boonville and attends a meeting in Comstock Hall.

entries.fullText:
At Boonville
Guest of Mrs Lucy A. Rinkle
her lovely daughter Miss Laura Rinkle
wrote letters all the
forenoon - slept in
P.M. and spoke
in Presbyterian Church
in evening - union meeting -
a full house - and
with the Pres. & Baptist
ministers expressed themselves
well pleased with speech -
Two Cornell graduates -
Misses Jessie & Nellie Burr
- ought to do good work
here - Mr & Mrs Byron P. Graves -
Mrs Helen M. Sperry - Rev & Mrs
Theodore F. Jessup - and
Miss Louise Snow -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was a guest of Mrs Lucy A. Rinkle in Boonville. She wrote letters in the morning, slept in the afternoon, and spoke at a union meeting in the evening. She received positive feedback from the Presbyterian and Baptist ministers. She also mentioned several people who were present at the meeting.

entries.fullText:
1st day - Jefferson Co.
Watertown - Miss Mills
Guest of Mrs W.W. Sherman
2 - Sherman Street -
meeting in splendid Opera
House - and packed -
Miss Asenith Coolidge
undoubtedly the best worker
here - but was left out
by Mrs Howell - at her
last member meeting -
& Rev Mrs Libby - Universalist
made the Chairman -
This is Gov Flowers
home - he left this A.M.
- no one invited him
to stay & introduce me -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a meeting in Watertown at the Opera House. She mentioned Miss Mills and Miss Asenith Coolidge, who was left out by Mrs Howell at her last member meeting. She also mentioned Rev Mrs Libby and Gov Flowers, who left in the morning without being introduced to Susan B. Anthony.

entries.fullText:
1st day - St Lawrence Co
Ogdensburg - Miss Hay
The Opera House -
guest of Mrs Mary Wadtle Rodger
34 - Kings Street. - Rev & Mrs
Rodgers & their little girl
Theodosia & boy Hewitt - all
splendid - Mrs Howell
arrived at 7. - ready to rest
for the tomorrow nights effort -
- It does seem strange - & is
if half our work on the people
were lost - because Miss Shaw
had to leave for her mother &
father - over 80 - at Big Rapids - Mich
The Presbyterian minister here
Rev. Miller - over 70 - & over
40 years preaching in Ogdensburg -
won't let his women pray in
his prayer meetings ! - the first one
I have heard of in years -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Ogdensburg, St. Lawrence Co. and stays with Mrs. Mary Wadtle Rodger. She meets with Miss Hay and the Rodgers family. Miss Shaw had to leave for her parents in Big Rapids, Mich. She also mentions the Presbyterian minister, Rev. Miller, who won't let women pray in his prayer meetings.

entries.fullText:
1st - day - Franklin Co
Malone - Mills & Hay -
Putnam Hall -
[Guest of Mrs May Waddle Rodgers
34 Kings Street] - Guests of
Mr Stevens & Mrs Lawrence
at the Cushman House
Mrs Paddock seems
the only at all live woman
- Had Hall packed
splendid audience -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Malone, Franklin Co. and stays with Mrs. May Waddle Rodgers. She meets with Mills and Hay and is a guest of Mr. Stevens and Mrs. Lawrence at the Cushman House. She mentions Mrs. Paddock as the only lively woman and had a packed audience at Putnam Hall.

entries.fullText:
1st - Day - Clinton Co.
Plattsburg -
Hannah L. Lansing -
wife Ed. - Plattsburg Sentinal
62 - Bridge Street -
Mrs Henry Barnard
135 North Margaret St
Mrs Howard living with Mrs B.
Mrs James B. Hall - Pres. County
W.C.T.U. called - said she had
promise of me - but was greatly
disappointed at my non-appearance -
The new Court House was filled
- Judge Campbell McLean - Dr
Wm McLeans son - brother of Judge
John & uncle Henry R. McLean of
Battenville - at meeting - his sister
Maria McLean Hartwell - not able
to come - I couldn't think of her
married name & didn't know that
Campbell had moved back from Wisconsin
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her activities in Plattsburg, including a meeting with the W.C.T.U. and a visit to the new Court House.

entries.fullText:
Essex County Mass meeting
Elizabethtown (crossed out) - Port Henry -
Guest of Mrs Mary F. Stimpson
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a mass meeting in Essex County and stays with Mrs. Mary F. Stimpson in Port Henry.

entries.fullText:
Warren - County Mass Meeting
Glens Falls -
entries.summaryText: Attended a mass meeting in Glens Falls, Warren County.

entries.fullText:
Annual meeting
Cincinnati
Guest of dear Mrs
W. W. Trimble -
1026 Covington - KY
Spoke this evening -
- audience not large
found Mrs H.J. Upton
at Mrs Trimbles -
entries.summaryText: Attended Ohio State W.S.A. annual meeting in Cincinnati, stayed with Mrs. W. W. Trimble in Covington, KY. Spoke to a small audience in the evening. Met Mrs. H.J. Upton at Mrs. Trimble's.

entries.fullText:
Ohio annual meeting
Miss Shaw spoke
this evening - I
spent morning at
their business meeting
Mrs Shrader - the
chief alive person -
Mrs Trimble had a
friend & daughter -
Mrs Campbell to tea -
and I took the train
at 8.30 for St Louis -
to spend tomorrow with
my dear friend Virginia
L. Minor - 3311 - Lucas Avenue
entries.summaryText: Attended Ohio annual meeting and spent time with friends before leaving for St Louis to visit Virginia L. Minor.

entries.fullText:
Ohio Annual Meeting -
Cincinnati - Ohio -
Dr Viola Swift - 131 Garfield Place
To be guest of Mrs W.W-
Trimble - Covington - KY
1026 - Madison Avenue
Cor - of Robbins Street
--
Mrs Carrie Chapman Catt
was the chief speaker this evening
--
I reached St Louis at 8 -
took Cab to Mrs Minors - found
her all alone - her next neighbor
had her girl cook & bring in both
breakfast & dinner - very nice -
so that Mrs M. & self visited all
the day long - & at 6.20 she went
with me to Station - where we found
Miss Shaw - we all took supper
together - then I saw dear
Mrs M. to the street car - to go back
to her all alone home - none but
her two parrots of gray & green -
to greet her there - dear Mr Minor
has been gone two years --
entries.summaryText: Attended Ohio Annual Meeting and spent time with friends before leaving for St Louis to visit Virginia L. Minor. Had dinner with Mrs. Minor and spent the day with her. Saw Miss Shaw and had supper together before leaving.

entries.fullText:
Kansas Campaign - Kansas City
5th Avenue Opera House - rough
enough - Miss Shaw &
self arrived at 9 A.M. & after
being sent hither & yon to see
people who didn't invite us
we were landed at our
good friends Mr & Mrs
Simpsons - who
with their one son & daughter
made us most welcome
Mrs Johns didn't arrive till
P.M. no session till 8 - I
then made my speech on
vital necessity of Planks in
Platforms - of Repub. & Populist
Platforms - It was given
under a fearful pressure of
opposition - Mrs Johns presiding -
never smiled, Miss Kimber Mrs
Js young double - whispered &
scolded - with Miss Anthony's
losing us a 1,000 votes by that -
- I never spoke under such a
pressure - all had been wheedled
into not demanding planks -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Kansas City for the Kansas Campaign and made a speech on the necessity of planks in platforms despite opposition.

entries.fullText:
Kansas City - Kansas
Opening Spring Campaign
for W.S. Constitutional Amendment
- Miss Shaw Mrs Chapman
latter arrived this A.M. - all
present at day meetings -
Mrs Johns, Miss Kimber &
seemingly every one vexed with
my last night's speech -
- Miss Shaw went to
Leavenworth at 6. P.M. - she
was ill all last night and to day -
-& Mrs J. classes her with me -
in killing the cause - by flatly
demanding Political party endorsement
of the amendment -
Mrs Chapman spoke this
evening - - had a full house
- Mrs Childs of Iowa - Mrs
Jenkins of Wyoming were
speakers also -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended the Opening Spring Campaign for W.S. Constitutional Amendment in Kansas City and Mrs. Chapman spoke in the evening with other speakers.

entries.fullText:
I took 10.20 train
for Leavenworth -
found brother D.R. & Anna
& nephew D.R. all gone
to Dr Page's Church - to
hear Miss Shaw preach -
& all were perfectly delighted.
Niece Maud was home .
to receive me - all went
to M.E. church to hear her -
- Mrs Chapman spoke
in Kansas City - -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Leavenworth and attends church with family members. Mrs. Chapman speaks in Kansas City.

entries.fullText:
The Women's Art League of
Leavenworth Kansas
Elizabeth R. Jones. - Mrs Dr. Jones -
invite me to address their League
this P.M. on "The Progressive Woman"
- Miss Shaw was also there
- both spoke & all seemed
pleased - but it was an
awfully hot place - even
sister remarked - Well aunt
Susan just the right words
come to you -
Mrs Chapman came
to brother Dan's - so all
three of us were there - &
all were delighted with
her - She spoke at the
Leav. Co. Mass Meeting - this
evening - & perfectly charmed Mr
Page - brother & nephew D.R. &
all - so all thought Miss Shaw
could never equal her - &
hence that the meeting had
better adjourn with Mrs
C's splendid speech -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks at the Women's Art League in Leavenworth and attends a mass meeting where Mrs. Chapman speaks.

entries.fullText:
May - 7&8 - The Ex. Com. Meeting
of National Council of Women - in
Parlor C. of the
Continental Hotel - Philadelphia
have appointed Mrs Upton & Mrs ??????
to represent the National A.W.S.A -
Lucy E. - my niece - took place of Mrs Upton
entries.summaryText: Attended the Ex. Com. Meeting of National Council of Women in Philadelphia and Mrs Upton & Mrs ?????? were appointed to represent the National A.W.S.A.

entries.fullText:
organized in P.M. - Political
Equality Club - woth Mrs
Cushing Pres -
at evening the Hall was
packed - jammed - & as
Miss Shaw proceeded every
one was carried out of
self - and Dr Page brother Dan
& all felt she even climaxed
Mrs Chapman - It is splendid
that we have two such
magnificent speakers - Each is best.
entries.summaryText: Organized a Political Equality Club in Leavenworth, Kansas and attended a packed meeting with Miss Shaw and Mrs Chapman as speakers.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Chapman went to
Laurence - and
Miss Shaw & I went to
Topeka - I was the
guest of Mr & Mrs
John Mulvane - he
was absent - so it was Mrs
Mulvane & her sister Mrs
Hamilton Hall was
packed - - But Mrs Johns
seems not a bit her old self -
- gives neither of us a
word in council - or
cooperation - Miss
Shaw guest of Mr &
Mrs Lyon - near
Washburn College -
entries.summaryText: Visited Topeka and stayed with Mr & Mrs John Mulvane, attended a packed meeting with Miss Shaw, and Mrs Johns was not cooperative.

entries.fullText:
In Topeka -
Mrs Chapman & Mrs
Jenkins the speakers
in Hamilton Hall this
evening - splendid audience
entries.summaryText: Mrs Chapman and Mrs Jenkins spoke in Hamilton Hall in Topeka to a splendid audience.

entries.fullText:
Went with Miss Shaw
to Burlingame - Osage Co.
meeting in Opera House -
Guest of Mr & Mrs
old settlers -
Miss Helen Kimber
here with us -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went with Miss Shaw to Burlingame in Osage Co. for a meeting in the Opera House. She was a guest of Mr. and Mrs. old settlers and Miss Helen Kimber was also with them.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw & self
went to Kansas City, Mo.
to nephew Arthur A.
Mosher's - niece Mattie
had written me inviting
Miss Shaw - so all was right
- though I had not received it -
Mattie was at station &
missed us -
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw and Susan B. Anthony went to Kansas City, Mo. to visit nephew Arthur A. Mosher's and niece Mattie, who had invited Miss Shaw but missed them at the station.

entries.fullText:
Kansas City - Mo -
a tremendous
audience in the
great auditorium
at 3. P.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a tremendous audience at the great auditorium in Kansas City, Mo. at 3 P.M.

entries.fullText: Left Rochester - with Mrs Greenleaf - 2.22 - the Empire State - for Albany - arrived 6.20 - stopped at The Antwerp - 156 State Street - Charles Fitch - Clerk of the Con. Con. called - also reporter of The Sun - Belle Howland met us at the station -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Rochester to Albany with Mrs Greenleaf, meets Charles Fitch and Belle Howland.

geographicalLocations: Constitutional Convention - in Assembly Chamber - Boarding at The Antwerp
entries.fullText: Albany - N.Y. State - Constitutional Convention - in Assembly Chamber - Boarding at The Antwerp - with Mrs Greenleaf -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is in Albany, New York attending the Constitutional Convention and staying at The Antwerp with Mrs Greenleaf.

entries.fullText: In Albany - Con. Con - The Suffrage com. voted to invite Miss Anthony to address them tomorrow Thursday P.M. 3[?]
entries.summaryText: The Suffrage committee at the Constitutional Convention in Albany voted to invite Miss Anthony to address them the following day.

entries.fullText: Queen Victoria is 74 years old this day - Every member of the suffrage Com. was present - & nearly all of the members of the Con. Con. - at the Hearing given S.B.A. in the Assembly Chamber - Isabel Howland & Hattie Mills & all declared she made a good statement of our case —
entries.summaryText: Queen Victoria's birthday, suffrage committee and members of the Con. Con. present at hearing.

entries.fullText: Albany - Con. Con - a large number of the County Petitions presented this A.M. The Suffrage Committee decided to give New York City a hearing on Thursday May 31st —
entries.summaryText: County petitions presented, suffrage committee decides to give New York City a hearing.

entries.fullText: Left Albany at 12.58 with Mrs Greenleaf for Rochester
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Albany for Rochester with Mrs Greenleaf.

entries.fullText: At home - Sister Mary & self - went to Church - it seemed to me that Mr Gannett spoke lower & more indistinctly than ever before - called at Dr Jonah Dolleys - & Mrs Greenleafs
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the day at home with her sister Mary, went to church, and visited Dr Jonah Dolleys and Mrs Greenleafs.

entries.fullText: Took the Empire State Train for Albany - to be there to see & hear the New York women went to the Antwerp -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony took the Empire State Train for Albany to see and hear the New York women. She also went to the Antwerp.

entries.fullText: The New Yorkers Dr Mary Putnam Jacobi - Mrs Sally Gibbons Emerson - et al - representing the Sherry Petition - Mrs Blake, Miss Keyser et al representing the old liners arrived at 1. P.M - Blake & Co went to Stanwix Jacobi & Co to the Delevan - The Assembly Chamber was well filled at 8 P.M - & Mrs Greenleaf introduced Dr J. first - who spoke over an hour in a most masterly style made wonderful impression - then came Mrs Blake - Miss Keyser & Miss Astor Chanler - a millionaire niece of Julia Ward Howes -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony met with various women representing petitions and old liners in Albany. Dr. J spoke first and made a wonderful impression, followed by Mrs. Blake, Miss Keyser, and Miss Astor Chanler.

entries.fullText:
Took the 8.20 train - Albany -
reached Rochester 2.25 - &
ran home & then to the new
Jewish Temple on
Gibbs Street - & heard Dr
Hirsch of Chicago - it
is a beautiful edifice &
the ceremonies beautiful -
Dr Myron Adams - Rev's Gannett
, Saxe, Kirkpatrick & several
Jewish Rabbis - assisted
Dr Max Lansburg - - then
home to supper - and on
board the Mich. Southern sleeper
at 9.25 for Chicago -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Albany to Rochester and attends the dedication of a new Jewish Temple.

entries.fullText:
Reached Chicago at
2. P.M - Mrs Avery
met me - and took
me a drive through
Lincoln Park - then
I went to bed for a sleep -
& at 6. was ready for
the dinner - & dear Mrs
Coonley was back from
the dedication of the
Field Museum at
Jackson Park -
I spent evening with
cousin Melissa - who
was just home from
Florida - while Mrs Avery
& Mrs Coonley attended
an entertainment -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Chicago and spends time with family while attending a dinner.

entries.fullText: Spent day visiting with Mrs Coonley - and Prentiss drove me to the Rock Island - 2. P.M. train - when I was the only one on the sleeper to Kansas City -
entries.summaryText: Visited with Mrs Coonley and Prentiss drove me to the Rock Island train to Kansas City.

entries.fullText: Arrived Kansas City just in time to catch the 8.20 Santa-Fee train - so reached Topeka about 11 Oclock - went to cousin Semantha Otis Dudley's house - She had made me promise to go to her - but on arriving was told Some California niece of Mr D's was coming - & so she took me to Dr Eva Harding's Office - where I spent that night - next to no sleep - and tomorrow meeting A.M. the Dr took me to her friends Dr Teffts -
entries.summaryText: Arrived in Kansas City and went to cousin Semantha Otis Dudley's house. Ended up spending the night at Dr Eva Harding's office due to unexpected guests. Meeting Dr Teffts tomorrow.

entries.fullText: At noon - this day - I went to Dr & Mrs Teffts - a nice home - The Republican Women's Association met this A.M. - Mrs Johns Pres - & a slimmer more nearly nothing lot of partisans I hope never to see - but for Miss Shaws & my rousing words - it looked as if they would not ask a plank - J. Ellen Foster - present - to declare she was a repub. 1st & a W.S. after - she spoke in Hamilton Hall in evening!!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting of the Republican Women's Association and hears J. Ellen Foster speak.

entries.fullText: before the Resolution Committee of which Eskridge was Chairman - he who was & 7 years ago & is to day one of the lowest & meanest opponents of woman's [enfranchisement?] - the Com. let us talk - but too closed ears - heads & hearts - determined to ignore our appeals -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks before the Resolution Committee, but they ignore her appeals.

entries.fullText: Miss Shaw was with me in the Repub. Women's meeting [Miss Shaw came this A.M. no last evening - I think it was] Wea. Wed. June 6, 1894 Ther. Republican Party State Nominating Convention - met at 12. noon - Miss Shaw myself & others had seats on the platform because - there could be no other place fixed for women - Judge Peters of Newton made Chairman - adjourned to appoint Committees till 3 P.M - during the recess brother D.R. & nephew D.R., Jr. called at Dr Teffts - but did not stay to a [?] the [?] - brother D.R. in his paper the L. Times has opposed Mr Morrill for Governor all along - just as we reached the Hall - he said brother Merritt had an encounter with a "bull" the day before - which resulted in the killing of the beast - & the injury of brother Merritt - this was all - & we were parted - so I worried until Friday A.M. when Dr Tefft telephoned to L. to learn - & Maude's reply was that all were well at the farm & home - at 5 P.M. Mrs Johns - Mrs Foster - Mrs Prentiss, myself, & Miss Shaw spoke
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends the Republican Party State Nominating Convention and speaks with Miss Shaw, brother D.R., nephew D.R., Jr., Mrs Johns, Mrs Foster, and Mrs Prentiss.

entries.fullText: Again we women went to the Repub. Con - to hear the Resolution Com. report - and it was unanimous & silent not even a thank you - nor a hope for the aid of the women of the state - - & not one of the 900 - members of the Committee entered a protest against this utter ignoring of the W.S. Amendment - So as a party - the Repub's say not even a word of hope for the success of our am't - nor for it's respectful consideration & discussion in their campaign meetings - which means the friends mouths are shut - & the enemies mouths opened - no words for us - but every [?] his speak against -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about attending the Republican Convention and the lack of support for the women's suffrage amendment.

entries.fullText: In Topeka at Dr Teffts - - 212 - West 8th Street -- Miss Shaw & self called at E.S.A. Head Quarters - Columbian Building - West 6th Street - to get Mrs Johns to tell us the attitude she thought the one for us to take now that the Repub's had ignored our W.S. Amendment in their platform - but she gave us nothing - she seems utterly at sea - with no power to her to do - but to drift with the Repub. Party -- Miss Shaw took train for Eureka at 11.25 - & after dinner - Mrs Tefft put me & my bag on board a College Avenue Car - & I went to Mrs T.L. Lyons - 1632 - College Ave. where Miss Shaw is to come Saturday noon & [I hope] Mrs Chapman Catt - Sunday A.M. and we three were all together there -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Topeka and her meeting with Mrs. Johns regarding the women's suffrage amendment. She also mentions her plans to meet with Miss Shaw and Mrs. Chapman Catt.

entries.fullText:
- In Topeka - Kansas -
At Mr & Mrs Tho's L. Lyons -
1633 - College Avenue -
- to speak in Hamilton Hall -
this evening with our Rev Anna H. Shaw
she on woman first & Repub &
Pop. afterwards - I on
Reasons why [both words underlined] neither of the
Dominant parties can put a
W.S. plank in platform -
Had a fine
crowd - Though the
rain fell in torrents
the thunder roared &
the lightning flashed -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spoke at Hamilton Hall in Topeka, Kansas with Rev Anna H. Shaw on the topic of women and politics. They discussed the Republican and Populist parties and why neither can support women's suffrage.

entries.fullText:
- In Topeka - at
Mrs Lyons -
Miss Shaw to preach
at the M.E. Church -
Dr Embry's - who is opposed.
- Mr & Mrs Lyon & son
went with Miss Shaw
- Mrs Chapman &
self remained at
home & talked over
the fearfully embarrassing
situation - [In
the evening Mrs Johns &
husband & Mr
drove out - but we
couldn't get Mrs J.
to make any statement
as to what & how she
would herself - or being
us present - the situation
in view of the Repub.
& no plank and the Pop & a plank]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a sermon by Rev Anna H. Shaw at the M.E. Church in Topeka, Kansas. She also discussed the political situation with Mrs. Chapman and Mrs. Johns, but Mrs. Johns did not provide any insight into her views on the Republican and Populist parties' stance on women's suffrage.

entries.fullText:
In Topeka-
The Progressive League
women held a stirring
meeting at 2. P.M -
& resolved to demand
plank of their party -
In evening they held a
meeting in Hamilton
Hall - packed - Mrs
Otis Presiding - Mrs
Chapman making the
principal speech -
entries.summaryText: The Progressive League women held a meeting and demanded a plank of their party. In the evening, they held another meeting in Hamilton Hall where Mrs. Otis presided and Mrs. Chapman made the principal speech.

entries.fullText:
The Populist Party
State Convention - &
we were all there in
force - in Hamilton Hall -
- We were all invited to
luncheon at Mrs
John Mulvanes -
The Populist Women
- Mrs Diggs their
leader - men in good
earnest - they followed
up the delegations & the
Resolution Committee -
never leaving them till
they got a goodly minority
pledged to report in
favor of a plank -
entries.summaryText: The Populist Party State Convention was held in Hamilton Hall and they were all invited to a luncheon at Mrs. John Mulvanes. The Populist Women, led by Mrs. Diggs, followed up the delegations and the Resolution Committee until they got a goodly minority pledged to report in favor of a plank.

entries.fullText:
The Resolution Com -
12 majority = reported ignoring
W.S. as did the Republicans
but - the 8 minority report -
after four hours discussion
was adopted - &
now begins the fray -
- the Repub's mad because
Miss Shaw & Miss Anthony
declared they'd "whoop"
for the party that whooped
for woman suffrage -
Mrs Johns came out to Mrs
Lyons this evening - but didn't
give us the slightest cue
as to how she would
have the status of our
case now put before the people
entries.summaryText: Discusses a Resolution Com and the Republican party's reaction to Miss Shaw and Miss Anthony's support for woman suffrage.

entries.fullText:
Miss Shaw tooke the
12. Oclock train last night =
and I took the 7.00
Santa Fee train this A.M.
the weather awfully hot
- reached Leavenworth
at 11- found brother D.R.
at the farm - stayed
this night
entries.summaryText: Describes travel to Leavenworth and staying with brother D.R. at the farm.

entries.fullText:
Took the 11.50 train
for Huron - found
both brothers - D.R. &
Merritt at the farm -
- took supper, slept, and
took breakfast & dinner [?]
at Mrs Watsons -
Found brother
Merritt pretty badly
used up with two
run-a-ways with
- horses & one attack
of a young bull - so
he decided it best
to go home & rest -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Huron and spends time with her brothers, one of whom is injured.

entries.fullText:
At Huron - I
spent entire forenoon
in Creamery watching
all the processes -
at 2 Oclock brother
Merritt & I started
for Fort Scott - Dannie
met us at train with
my satchel - No
train out from K.C.
until 9.30 - P.M. So
took supper & waited
- & their engine broke
& we didn't reach
Fort Scott till 1. A.M -
found May L. Brunt
& Anna - all well -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends time in Huron and then travels to Fort Scott to meet with friends.

entries.fullText:
At Fort Scott -
had nice call
on Dr Sarah Hall -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a nice call on Dr Sarah Hall in Fort Scott on June 17, 1894.

entries.fullText:
Took the 7.20 A.M
train for Leavenworth
Weather hot - the
Missouri river raging
high - "June rise" -
went up in Burlington
& crossed the New
Bridge - water precious
near to being even
with the track -
entries.summaryText: On June 18, 1894, Susan B. Anthony took a train to Leavenworth and crossed the New Bridge over the Missouri river, which was raging high due to the 'June rise'.

entries.fullText: Brother D.R. didn't come home - but the weather was too hot for me to go up to Huron - much as I wanted to talk over matters with him -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Brother D.R. not coming home and the hot weather preventing her from going to Huron to talk over matters with him.

entries.fullText: Left Leavenworth on the 4 Oclock P.M. Rock Island train for Chicago -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about leaving Leavenworth on a train for Chicago.

entries.fullText:
Reached Chicago
at 10 - and
took the Michigan
Southern train
at 10.30 for Rochester -
- being too hot -
& too dirty to go
& see dear Mrs
Gross - couldn't
get a sleeper - or
lower berth - so went
into common car - there
met Dan. M. Anthony of
Rochester - & Mrs Isabel J
Barrows of Boston - she
wouldn't take upper berth
this hot weather - so
we chatted all day & all night -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony reached Chicago and took the Michigan Southern train to Rochester. She met Dan. M. Anthony of Rochester and Mrs Isabel J Barrows of Boston on the common car.

entries.fullText:
At Buffalo - at
1 A.M. we changed
cars - & on reaching
Rochester at 2 A.M.
an hour behind time
Mrs Barrows seemed
fast asleep - so I
left her - It was so
light when I reached
17 Madison St - that I
sat on the steps & read
the morning paper -
For the first time in
my many trips to Kansas -
I took only a satchel
a small telescope -
but I suffered more
from the need of cool
clothing than all the
trouble from a trunk -
- Found sister Mary
not expecting me till
the next day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Rochester an hour behind time and left Mrs Barrows sleeping. She sat on the steps of 17 Madison St and read the morning paper. She found sister Mary not expecting her until the next day.

entries.fullText:
-
Reporter from
every paper came to
interview me on my
"going over to the
Populists" - yesterday -
so that this A.Ms -
Dem & Chronicle &
The Herald - and
this afternoons
Post Express & Union
Advertiser - each &
all had my report
of myself - one
would think I
had committed
the I'm against
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was interviewed by reporters from various newspapers about her 'going over to the Populists'.

entries.fullText:
Went to Church -
----
against the Holy
Ghost - in thanking
the Populists for their
good promise - &
saying I preferred
them no matter
what their financial
vagaries - with
justice to women -

-to the Republicans no
matter what their financial
wisdom - without justice
to women -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to church and expressed her preference for the Populists over the Republicans due to their stance on justice for women.

entries.fullText: At Home
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on June 25, 1894, written at home.

entries.fullText: At Home
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on June 26, 1894, written at home.

entries.fullText: At home
entries.summaryText: At home

entries.fullText: At home
entries.summaryText: At home

entries.dateText:
Met Anna Shaw - at train for NY
[?] - her route is cape Cod -
From [?] at 8.25 A.M.
entries.fullText:
Met Anna Shaw - at train for NY
[?] - her route is cape Cod -
From [?] at 8.25 A.M.
entries.summaryText: Met Anna Shaw at train station for NY and discussed her route to Cape Cod.

entries.fullText:
Our eldest sister -
Guelma P. Anthony McLeans
76th birth day - seventy six
years ago - was our dear
mothers first birth agony - of
her whole number of eight -!!
Weather very hot -
heard Mr Garnet preach -
at eve called at Mrs
Backalls after- & the Garnetts -
- the talk on 'going over to
the Populists" - no one
seems to see that woman's
first work is freedom & the
franchise - that the man &
the party that will help her -
is the truest & best - not only
for woman herself - but for
all - the state & the nation -
because justice to half the
people - must be done - before
honesty can come between
man & man - until the
half are honest to the other
half - the habit makes them distant
with each other
entries.summaryText: Celebrated Guelma P. Anthony McLeans' 76th birthday, attended church, and discussed women's suffrage and politics with Mr. Garnet and Mrs. Backalls.

entries.fullText:
At home - still hot -
- still
entries.summaryText: No significant events mentioned.

entries.fullText:
Letter from brother D.R. he
has remained at the farm -
Huron - 17 - days with only
one visit at home -
Annie & Maude went up
& spent the hour & seven minutes
Saturday - June 30th - the day he wrote -
entries.summaryText: Susan receives a letter from her brother D.R. who has been at the farm in Huron for 17 days with only one visit home. Annie and Maude went to visit him on June 30th.

entries.fullText:
[Denver - Colorado - to
join in celebrating their 1st Fourth
of July day of freedom to women
Have accepted invitation to
be the guest of Mrs
Catherine G. Patterson
Pennsylvania & 11th Avenues !!]
Decided not to go
entries.summaryText: Susan plans to go to Denver, Colorado to celebrate the first Fourth of July day of freedom for women, and has accepted an invitation to be the guest of Mrs. Catherine G. Patterson. However, she ultimately decides not to go.

entries.fullText: Wea. Sat. July 7, 1894 Ther.
Went to hear Mr Gannett preach - Frederick Hosmer preached in Mr Gannetts pulpit -
entries.summaryText: Attended church service and heard Mr. Gannett and Frederick Hosmer preach.

entries.fullText:
Took the 2.25 Empire
State Train for Albany -
found Mrs Greenleaf -
& Hattie at the Antwerp
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony took a train to Albany and met with Mrs. Greenleaf and Hattie at the Antwerp.

entries.fullText:
Albany -
Mrs Almy
arrived this A.M. -
Mrs Blake in city - &
Mrs Greenleaf invited
members - who are our
W.S. friends to meet us
in Assembly Parlors -
14 came - Howell was
with us - & the men
gave satisfactory talks
quite hopeful -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony met with Mrs. Almy, Mrs. Blake, and Mrs. Greenleaf in Albany. They invited members of their W.S. friends to meet them in Assembly Parlors. 14 people came and Howell was with them. The men gave satisfactory talks and they were quite hopeful.

entries.fullText: In Albany - warm & muggy - with no feeling of usefulness in my staying & adding one to those who must be uncomfortable - The Unitarian Pic-nic this day - sister Mary went & enjoyed it - to the Bay -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about feeling useless in Albany due to the warm and muggy weather. She mentions her sister Mary attending a Unitarian Pic-nic in the Bay.

entries.fullText: Left Albany on the 11.20 - Empire state train for Rochester - & left dear Mrs Greenleaf & Harriet May Mills to swelter on there looking after the Con. Con -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Albany on a train for Rochester, leaving Mrs Greenleaf and Harriet May Mills behind to look after the Con. Con.

entries.fullText: At home
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote a short entry stating that she was at home.
Susan B. Anthony wrote a short entry, but did not provide any details.

entries.fullText:
This was Mr Gannetts
last Sunday - They go -
to Poultneyville - Wayne Co
for vacation -
entries.summaryText: Mr. Gannett's last Sunday plans to go to Poultneyville, Wayne Co for vacation.

entries.fullText:
Summoned to appear
surrogate Adlington's
Office - 10 Oclock -
this A.M - to witness
settlement of estate of
Eliza J. Cook - with her
Executor - Russell W. Somers -
She willed me $1,000 -
entries.summaryText: Summoned to appear at surrogate Adlington's office to witness settlement of estate of Eliza J. Cook with her executor, Russell W. Somers. She willed me $1,000.

entries.fullText: Niece Julie came this forenoon & spent the day - [& night] - Went down to surrogates office again but to have matters postponed to Aug 20th Rev Gannett - Mrs Gannett Mr Hosmer - Mrs May Hallowell - Sarah Willis Anna Barnes and Anna C. Mott (Connie) here to tea - very, very hot - but still a very pleasant visit - Niece Julie had engaged to go back to Minnie Sacketts to go to the Lake - so we were very sorry not to have her here to see the guests - & to sing for them too -
entries.summaryText: Niece Julie came to visit and spent the day with Susan B. Anthony and other guests. They went to the surrogates office and had a pleasant visit despite the hot weather.

entries.fullText: Julie remained at Minnie Sacketts [to go to Mainton Reach] this day - She is having Jolly times - Minnie gives her whole time A Telegram came from her father - saying the R.R. were now safe & for her to start for San Diego as soon as she could & later a dispatch came from May Maxwell that she wanted May & Susan & Julie to come to Batavia tomorrow -
entries.summaryText: Julie stayed at Minnie Sackett's and received a telegram from her father. May Maxwell also invited Susan, May, and Julie to come to Batavia the next day.

entries.fullText:
Niece Julie & self
took the 9.45 train
for Batavia - found
Aunt Sophia Fitch
McLean & her daughter
Mary McLean Maxwell
at home - we took
dinner & tea - and
returned on the 8.25
train - Julie remained
with us this night -
- Sister Mary - after our
early breakfast rushed
over to Minnie Sacketts to
get Julie to the Station -
while I went to Dr
Requas to have gold
Plate fixed -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and her niece Julie took a train to Batavia to visit Aunt Sophia Fitch McLean and her daughter Mary McLean Maxwell. They had dinner and tea before returning home.

entries.fullText:
In forenoon - I went
with Julia to call on
Miss Maria Porter - now
almost 89 - - on Mrs
Hallowell & Mrs Willis &
then to Mrs Gould's
on Sophia Street - then
home to dinner - after
which Julie rested & slept
and in evening - Kittie
Shields, Lottie Anthony &
Lillian Coleman came - &
Julie Sang - all say her
voice is lovely - & Lottie
& Kittie played the Piano
- & all enjoyed it -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited Miss Maria Porter, Mrs. Hallowell, Mrs. Willis, and Mrs. Gould in the morning. In the evening, Kittie Shields, Lottie Anthony, and Lillian Coleman came over and Julie sang while Lottie and Kittie played the piano.

entries.fullText:
Julie spent the
eearly part of forenoon
with us - the rain
poured - at last I
went with her to
Minnie Sacketts - while
she put on dark
dress - & then went
with her to Hattie
Baker Virga's & left
her there -
entries.summaryText: Julie spent time with Susan B. Anthony and then went to Minnie Sackett's to change clothes before going to Hattie Baker Virga's.

entries.fullText:
Didn't go to the
Lucy service - but
sister Mary did -
Julie at Minnie
Sacketts - getting
ready to take
train tomorrow night -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony did not attend the Lucy service, but her sister Mary did. Julie was at Minnie Sackett's getting ready to take a train the next night.

entries.fullText:
Great niece Guelma - niece Maggie
McLean Baker's only daughter -
took the 10.25 night train -
Mich. Central - for Chicago - & then
on Santa Fe train to San Diego -
She will be [?] on Aug. 8.
Sister Mary & self went
to Minnie Sacket Smith's
to see Julie off - Ticket
agent Kaulfleish & wife
& [Sunday?] of the Sacketts
went to station with her
at 10.25 - so Mary & self
said good by & returned
home to think of her -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's great niece and niece Maggie McLean Baker's daughter took a train from Michigan to Chicago and then to San Diego. Susan and her sister Mary went to see Julie off at the station.

entries.fullText:
Niece Julie
arrives Chicago at
2 P.M - Louis
Hensner to see
her on the Santa Fe
train at 9.30 P.M.
