entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's niece Julie arrived in Chicago and was met by Louis Hensner at the Santa Fe train station.

entries.fullText:
Niece Julie is now speeding
her way through Kansas
on the Santa Fe train
Walked to May Hallowells
- out riding - then to Miss
Porters - Fremont St - & at
9. came home street cars - &
with Miss Emma Hay - took
a glass of Lemonade in the
W.C.T.U. Festival in our
Madison St Park - very nice -

fearfully hot -
entries.summaryText: Niece Julie is traveling through Kansas, Susan walked to May Hallowell's and Miss Porters, and attended the W.C.T.U. Festival in Madison St Park.

entries.fullText:
Sister Mary left for Warsaw
or Silver Lake at - 7.20 -
A Postal from
niece Julie - mailed
at Joliet Ill - saying
all well so far -
entries.summaryText: Sister Mary left for Warsaw or Silver Lake and Susan received a postal from niece Julie mailed from Joliet Ill.

entries.fullText:
awfully hot
Fairport - Monroe Co - N.Y.
M.E. Church - guest of
Mr & Mrs Anson L. Beardsley
& Mrs H.M. Goodell - [?] W.C.T.U.
- Mrs Wilson has charge the
Con. Con. petition - church
filled with women - not
a score of men among them
- no proper ventilation - &
the heat was smothering -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a hot day in Fairport, NY, where she attended a church event with mostly women and no proper ventilation.

entries.fullText:
Left Fairport on the
9.45 train - Grand
niece Julie - niece
Maggie McLean Baker's
only daughter - was to
reach her home - San
Diego - California - this A.M.
after five nights & four
days steady going westward
- and what a joy in that
home - Sister Guelma's husband -
Aaron M. McLean - only surviving
child - Margaret - & husband Geo. L.
Baker & their four children -
Henry Anthony - M.D. - Surgeon
on the City of Peking - Thomas
King, Guelma McL. and
Lawrence McLean Baker - Oh
to be a mouse in the walls
of that Sandiego Home to
see & hear the joy!!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her journey to San Diego to visit family, including her grandniece Julie and her sister Guelma's family, and expresses joy at being there.

entries.fullText:
Sister Mary went to
Church Parlor - to hear
Miss Otis - read her
essay - reported
it excellent - I wrote
letters - and at 2.20 both
of drove to State Industrial
School - in State Carriage
& with State driver & horses -
- we stopped - after Chapel -
& took tea with Miss
Keough - acting Superintendent
of Girls Department - in absence .
of Miss Craig - then home
& wrote niece Louise, Wendell
& Frank Mosher - relative to
the Life Insurance of their
father -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Sister Mary going to Church Parlor, visiting State Industrial School, and writing letters to her niece Louise, Wendell, and Frank Mosher.

entries.fullText:
Went to Surrogates office
Judge Adlington - hoping
to get the $1,000 bequest of
Mr Eliza Clapp - but the
Lawyers - Whittley & Carnahan
for City Charity - and Humane
Societys - which are to have the
residuals were not ready
to pay off the legacies - so
the case is put of to Sept. 5.
I think -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about going to Surrogates office to get a bequest but the lawyers were not ready to pay off the legacies.

entries.fullText: Ther.
entries.summaryText: Entry about Arthur A. Mosher.

entries.fullText:
Arthur A. Mosher - sent
statement - & I wrote Wendell,
Frank & Wendell - Louise --
entries.summaryText: Entry about Arthur A. Mosher, Wendell, Frank, Wendell, and Louise, and a statement sent.

entries.fullText: Wea. Sat. Aug. 4, 1894 Ther.

Mrs E.L. Coit - of Oswego
M.E. Minister's wife - took
8 Oclock breakfast with us
& I went with her to the
State Industrial School
& spent the day - & at
evening - attended M.E.
1st = Church & heard Mr
Coit preach -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day with Mrs E.L. Coit at the State Industrial School and attends M.E. 1st Church in the evening to hear Mr. Coit preach.

entries.fullText:
Wea. Mon. Aug. 6, 1894 Ther.

this day - not tomorrow

this day - at 2 Oclock P.M.

Geo. H. Ball -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about meeting with Geo. H. Ball on August 6, 1894.

entries.fullText:
Wea. Tues. Aug. 7, 1894 Ther.

Keuka College $50

this day - not tomorrow

this day - at 2 Oclock P.M.

Geo. H. Ball -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about receiving $50 from Keuka College on August 7, 1894.

entries.fullText:
[Keuka College - Pen Yan -
George Hall - Ball - lecture
at 2 P.M. --]
--

Grand niece - Guelma
McLean Baker is 19 years
old this day - dear
sister Hannah went
over to see darling
Maggie through - feeble
& unable as she was -

Left Pen Yan - Mrs John & Julia
Sheppard's - at 7.30 - & reached
Albany at 2 P. went to
the Antwerp - dined - & to
the Con. Con. in evening to hear
the discussion on Woman
Suffrage amendment - Hon
Edward Lauterbach made
splendid speech - dear Emily
Howland - Came - so we had Isabel
Hattie & Mrs Greenleaf - all there --
I slept in Hall bedroom -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about attending a lecture at Keuka College in Pen Yan, visiting family, and attending a discussion on Woman Suffrage amendment in Albany.

entries.fullText:
Albany - Antwerp -
Mrs Charlotte A. Cleveland - of
Perry & daughter came -
- A second Redemption
this
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Mrs. Charlotte A. Cleveland and a second Redemption in Albany.

entries.fullText:
Left Albany at 4. P.M.
for Cattskill - the guest of
dear Emily Howland -
Mrs Greenleaf went home
on Empire State - 11.20 - so
Isabel & Hattie & I went to
C. with Emily Howland
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Albany and arrived at Cattskill to stay with Emily Howland.

entries.fullText:
Emily Howland her
niece Isabel - Harriet
May Mills - & another
niece of Emilys - Miss Maude
Howland - all went to
the Cattskill Mountain House
then took a carriage & drove
to Twilight Park - & to
Eagles Nest - Miss Willards
mountain home - but
she & Anna Gordon - had
gone to New York to meet
Lady Henry Somerset -
and as we reached
the foot of the mountain
train we met them going
up - It was a big
day for us all -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the day with Emily Howland, Isabel, Harriet May Mills, and Miss Maude Howland, visiting various locations in Cattskill. They also met Miss Willard and Anna Gordon, who had gone to New York to meet Lady Henry Somerset.

entries.fullText: Took dinner at Emily's Sister in Laws - Mrs Louise Howlands - one son & one daughter at home returned to Woodmen & had quite a suffrage talk with the boarders there
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had dinner at Emily's Sister in Laws and returned to Woodmen where she had a suffrage talk with the boarders.

entries.fullText: Left Cattskill at 3. P.M. - for Albany stopped at Mrs Laurie Dunham's 20 - Lancaster St -- Albany N.Y - a nice place --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Cattskill for Albany and stopped at Mrs Laurie Dunham's, a nice place.

entries.fullText:
My dear friend Mrs
Virginia L. Minor of
3311 - Locust Avenue -
St Louis - Mo - died
this day - & left me
so I learned days
after $1,000 -
The discussion of our
amendment resumed
in Con. Con. this evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's friend, Mrs. Virginia L. Minor, passed away and left her $1,000. The discussion of their amendment resumed in Con. Con. that evening.

entries.fullText: Wea. Thur. Aug. 16, 1894 Ther.

Ex. Governor Robinson
Charles Robinson
of Kansas - died this day -
- he left his entire estate
to his wife - & at
her death the most of it
to go to the Kansas State
University - at Lawrence
entries.summaryText: Ex. Governor Robinson and Charles Robinson of Kansas died. The estate was left to his wife and at her death, most of it will go to the Kansas State University in Lawrence.

entries.fullText:
Casadaga Camp meeting -
Lily Dale - Guest of
Dear Mr & Mrs T Skidmore
I spoke in A.M. and
Miss Shaw in P.M -
- we spent evening reading
immense package of
letters - about Kansas -
from our Treasurer
Mrs H.T. Upton -
In closing - She says
"What are you going to do
with the $100,000 - left
you by Mrs Minor -
- This was the first
intimation I had heard
of her illness or death -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a camp meeting in Casadaga and spends time with friends in Lily Dale. She speaks in the morning and her colleague Miss Shaw speaks in the afternoon. They spend the evening reading letters from the treasurer about Kansas. Susan is surprised to learn about the death of Mrs. Minor and the $100,000 left to them.

entries.fullText:
Left Lily Dale at 10.50 -
reached Rochester 2.25 -
- found that Miss Shaw
had gone strait through
without stopping off -
As Sister Mary had
seen nothing of the
death of Mrs Minor &
as Press items were
flying of her having
left $100,000 to Miss Anthony
I sent telegram to
Mr Minor Meriwether
asking of him - but no
reply came -
entries.summaryText: Miss Shaw goes straight through Rochester without stopping off. Miss Anthony is rumored to have been left $100,000 by Mrs. Minor.

entries.fullText: Getting no reply from Mr Meriwether - I wrote the Probate Judge - the neighbor who so kindly served dinner for us that 3d May day - also Mrs E.A. Meriwether
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about writing to the Probate Judge and a neighbor named Mr. Meriwether who did not reply. She also mentions Mrs. E.A. Meriwether.
Susan B. Anthony did not write anything on this day.

entries.fullText:
To day received letter
from Mr Minor Meriwether
containing copy of dear
Mrs Minors will -
entries.summaryText: Received a letter from Mr Minor Meriwether containing a copy of Mrs Minors will.

entries.fullText:
received reply from
Mr Meriwether also
some mail a copy
of will from the Judge
entries.summaryText: Received reply from Mr Meriwether and a copy of a will from the Judge.

entries.fullText: Wea. Sat. Sept. 1, 1894 Ther.

At home
Worked with letters
& answering all the
day - & at 6.25 -
was at Station
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the day at home working with letters and answering them. Later in the day, she went to the station.

entries.fullText:
State Industrial schools
opened today - & the experiment
of having the primary boys - nearly
200 our of the 600 - put into
school together with the younger
girls - has begun - and I
did not keep my promise
to Supt Craig - to be present
to see the coming together!!
Mrs. Carrie Chapman Call - came
last night = & we talked all
day - over Kansas - & the
national work - She has
a marvelously level head!!
She left on the 10:45 - train for
Chicago & begins Fall campaign
"Non-Partisan"- in - Kansas-
on the 12th-
entries.summaryText: State Industrial schools opened today and primary boys were put into school together with younger girls. Mrs. Carrie Chapman Call came to visit and they talked about Kansas and national work. She left for Chicago to begin a Fall campaign.

entries.fullText:
The Attorneys Whittlesy &
Carnahan promise to be
ready to pay off the Clapp
Legacies this A.M. - [?]
Whittlesy - attorney for the
City Charities society - wasn't
ready so the payment
was postponed again
to Oct. 2d- Oh the
delays of the law - &
the utter heedlessness of
the lawyers as to a
woman's time-
entries.summaryText: The payment of Clapp Legacies was postponed again due to the attorney's unpreparedness.

entries.fullText: Wea. FRI. SEPT. 7, 1894 Ther
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated September 7, 1894.

entries.fullText:
East Hamlin - Monroe Co -
M. E. Church -
D. R. Griffith -
Miss Hays & Mrs Greenleaf here
all the A.M. planning lecture tour for
Miss H. & self - Clara B. Colby came
at 12.30 - We talked - mainly -
Kansas entanglement till 5 P.M.
then & made ready & took the
6. Oclock - Rome & Watertown R.R.
arriving at East Hamlin at. 7.
- with a cup of tea - Japan -
- with Mrs Jennie Griffith - was
on platform - Free Baptist - at. 8.
with a large audience - but
very unfamiliar with the
first principles - a Society was
organized - with Mrs. Fannie
Northrup - Pres - Mrs.
Jennie Griffith Pres. - Mrs
Amelia Blossom - Secy - and Mrs
Ann Madden - Treasurer
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated September 8, 1894, written in East Hamlin, Monroe Co. Susan B. Anthony plans a lecture tour with Miss H. and Clara B. Colby. She arrives in East Hamlin via Rome & Watertown R.R. and attends a Free Baptist event where a society is organized.

entries.fullText:
Took 6. Oclock breakfast -
Master - 18 - Henry Tenney of
Hamlin Center - drove me
into Brockport - where I took the
train at 9.05 - They thought it was
to be 8.30 - distance 10 miles -
though a lovely street of good
farmers to the Ridge Road - then
equally lovely west to Clarkson
Corners. Then a mile south to
Brockport - all thickly settled
& looking prosperous all along -
. reached the house at 10 - A.M -
& sat down to work -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Hamlin Center to Brockport, noting the prosperous and settled areas along the way.
Susan B. Anthony is in Wolcott.

entries.fullText:
Wea. TUES. SEPT. 11, 1894 Ther.
Newark
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated September 11, 1894 from Newark.

entries.fullText:
Wea. WED. SEPT. 12, 1894 Ther.
Frankfort
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated September 12, 1894 from Frankfort.

entries.fullText:
Wea. THUR. SEPT. 13, 1894 Ther.
Little Falls
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated September 13, 1894 from Little Falls.

entries.fullText:
Wea. FRI. SEPT. 14, 1894 Ther.
Amsterdam
did not attend this
Miss Hay & Mrs Colby -
I went back to Rochester
to visit with brother
D.R. who arrived
from Pittsburg Grand
Army National meeting
this morning - before
I arrived
entries.summaryText: Journal entry dated September 14, 1894 from Amsterdam. Susan B. Anthony did not attend something, visited Rochester to see her brother D.R. who arrived from the Grand Army National meeting in Pittsburg.

entries.fullText: Ther.
entries.summaryText: Entry on September 15, 1894, written at home.

entries.fullText: Ther.
entries.summaryText: Entry on September 16, 1894, written at home.

entries.fullText:
Left home- at 9.50 -
Anna Shaw went Station
with me - she was going
to take 10.20 train to
Wolcott- It did seem
too cruel that I must go
away from home & leave
brother D.R. right in
the middle of his weeks
visit with us
Went on special
Republican train - Mrs
Greenleaf with me-
Mother at Dr
Strongs Santarium-
found Miss Hay
there before us-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left home and went to the station with Anna Shaw. She took a special Republican train with Mrs. Greenleaf and found Miss Hay at Dr. Strong's Sanitarium.

entries.fullText:
The Republican State
nominating Convention -
Saratoga Springs - N.Y
in Convention Hall - a
large auditorium
seats - 5,000 - but devoid
of all acoustic
properties - a good [?]
at noon Mr
Lauterbach - Mrs
Greenleaf & self
all together were
allowed 5 - (not each-
but all - before the
Repub Resolution Com-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended the Republican State nominating convention at Saratoga Springs, NY with Mr. Lauterbach and Mrs. Greenleaf. The convention hall lacked acoustic properties.

entries.fullText: Mrs Harvey of Brooklyn - took Mrs Greenleaf & self to call on Mrs Spencer Trask. nee Nichols. of Brooklyn- - a lovely & cultured woman in a palace home - thence to Judge Marvins & his daughters Mrs Payne & Mrs Shumaker - & their daughters - Judge Marvin & Judge Lackett, oldest & first families - cotemporaries with Judge Wm Hay - very old friend - who always helped along our work in Saratoga & Albany - At evening spoke to the guests of the House - in the parlors. - Miss Willard & Lucy Henry followed me with nice talks - Mrs Greenleaf at close - had a score of women gather round her - while she told of efforts long & trying - which women had to put forth to gain any point -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits various people in Brooklyn and speaks to guests at a house in Saratoga and Albany about the efforts women had to put forth to gain any point.

entries.fullText: Left Dr Strongs at 12.50 - - Miss Willard & Miss Gordon to go to Churchville - then to Chicago - Lucy Henry to return to Cattskill - & Twilight Park - Miss Hay - Mrs Greenleaf & self for a meeting at Ballston Springs - very hard rain- all day- no audience in P.M. - a very nice one in evening in their new Court House - built but four years ago - Mrs Forbes the Pres. W.C.T.U - helped our meeting along - I stopped at Medbury Hotel - Mrs L. & Miss Hay slept at Mrs - Brother Daniel R. left Rochester for home to night I have felt very uncomfortable that I must be away these days Since Monday last & when he could be with us in our own home - but the fates [?] to compel me away -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a meeting at Ballston Springs and stops at Medbury Hotel.

entries.fullText:
Miss Hay - Mrs G. & self returned
to Saratoga - Dr. Strong's - on
10. A.M. train - met
there Mr Eddy - eldest son
of George Eddy with whom niece
Maude travelled in Europe
the summer of 1892 - his
father died recently - & he
is going to India - a Missionary
- After dinner - we took
a two hours drive - for
$2 - in a one horse coupe -
a lovely day -- Miss Hay
a splendid manager
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony returns to Saratoga and meets with Miss Hay and Mrs. G. They take a drive and meet Mr. Eddy, who is going to India as a missionary.

entries.fullText:
Mrs G. Miss Hay & self
had meeting this evening at
Mechanicsville - in
M.E. Church - and
returned to Saratoga on
midnight train -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony, Mrs. G., and Miss Hay have a meeting in Mechanicsville and return to Saratoga on the midnight train.

entries.fullText:
My unitarians arrived
Rev. E.E. Hale preached
this evening in Con. Hall -
Sisters & nieces of
U.S. Senator Hoar
of Mass - at Dr Strongs
entries.summaryText: Susan attended a unitarian sermon by Rev. E.E. Hale at Con. Hall, where she met the sisters and nieces of U.S. Senator Hoar of Mass.

entries.fullText:
[Democratic State
Convention - in
Convention Hall -]
Prof Peabody of
Harvard made
the opening address
this evening - Senator
Hoar of Mass
presiding
This evening Mrs Blake
Mrs Greenleaf & self
appeared before the
Dem. resolution Com -
Lieut Gov. Shehan Chair
entries.summaryText: Susan attended the Democratic State Convention at Convention Hall, where Prof Peabody of Harvard made the opening address and Senator Hoar of Mass presided. Later, Susan and two other women appeared before the Democratic resolution committee, chaired by Lieut Gov. Shehan.

entries.fullText:
Democratic State
Convention in
Convention Hall - in
Saratoga Springs
[Mrs Polake arrived
- &]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the Democratic State Convention in Saratoga Springs and mentions the arrival of Mrs Polake.

entries.fullText:
Miss Hay & self had
to leave - before the
nomination - to go to
Illion - where
we had a very good
meeting - the guests
of Mrs M. A. Bellinger -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about leaving the Democratic State Convention early and attending a meeting in Illion as guests of Mrs M. A. Bellinger.

entries.fullText:
Made the Journey
to Northville - where
we spent the night -
to take the A.M.
train for Wells -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Northville and spends the night before taking a train to Wells.

entries.fullText:
Hamilton County
Mass meeting - the 60th
making me - for the first
& only time in my whole
44 years campaigning - com
pass the entire sixty counties
in one & the same year -
the meeting at
Wells
Miss Hay & self - gues at
the - Hotel --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a mass meeting in Hamilton County and stays at a hotel in Wells with Miss Hay.

entries.fullText: Wea. Sat. Sept. 29, 1894 Ther.

At Home -
Didn't go to Church - but
to dinner with Sister Mary
to Mrs Mary Thayer Sanfords -
at 2 - to meet a young
Oriental - & at 2 P.M.
went to hear him talk on
the women of India - which
proved their Jewish idea
of her impurity - &c -
Augusta Coleman
Barbite - gave the world
a boy at 9 - this A.M --
This is the 11th birth day
of Hattie Stanton - Nora -
This is the 80th birth
day of Mrs - ought to be
Prof. Lucinda H. Stone
of Kalamazoo - Michigan -
& I forgot to write her my
greetings for her grand work —
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day at home, attends a dinner at Mrs. Mary Thayer Sanfords, and hears a young Oriental man speak about the women of India. Augusta Coleman Barbite gives birth to a boy. It is the 11th birthday of Hattie Stanton Nora and the 80th birthday of Mrs. Lucinda H. Stone of Kalamazoo, Michigan.

entries.fullText: at 5. this P.M. the dear Augusta - was siezed with pain in bowels - & & from this on - despair grew apace -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Augusta experiencing pain in her bowels and growing despair.
Susan B. Anthony writes a brief entry with no significant information.

entries.fullText:
The $1,000 - bequest of Mrs
Clapps - promised to be
paid this - day - postponed
from Sept. 5th G M
Whittlesey's neglect to get his
society - the city Charities - part
done - Judge Carnahan
had Humane Society ready -
- But they were not set
in [in] order - & now said
the money would be ready
on Friday A.M -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Clapps' $1,000 bequest is postponed due to G M Whittlesey's neglect.

entries.fullText:
At home -
Called to see how
Augusta Colman was -
at 8.20 - word very
low - then went to
Mrs Fullams - & returned
- went again to Mrs C's
& found the dear girl
almost gone - the
mother, sister & husband
all frantic - Her Doctor
appalled - It was
like a clap of thunder
from a clear sky - no
apparent cause of the
trouble - Bloody Dysentery!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Augusta Colman who is very ill and later finds out she has Bloody Dysentery.

entries.fullText: Went for the money but - still it didn't come - All are stunned with the death of Augusta - wife of John Barbite -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about not receiving money and the death of Augusta, wife of John Barbite.

entries.fullText: [Poor Augusta Colman died at 1. P.M. this day - - with no visible cause] -In P.M. Bought R.R. & sleeper tickets & got baggage check to go to New York on the 9.25 - Sunday night train - but on getting home from Colman's at 10 - found telegram from Mrs Blake [?elling] me - this neessitated rushing over to Station Sunday A.M - & disposing of tickets - -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the sudden death of Augusta Colman and her travel plans being disrupted due to a telegram from Mrs. Blake.

people: Rev's Stewart - Baptist & Rev Gardner - Presbyterian
entries.fullText:
-
At Home -
Funeral at 2. P.M -
an immense crowd -
Rev's Stewart - Baptist
& Rev Gardner - Presbyterian
officiated -
What a
slight distance
between perfect
health - seemingly -
& death - surely -
entries.summaryText: Attended a funeral at home with an immense crowd and two reverends officiating.

entries.fullText:
-
At Home
Went to see
Dr Mulligan - &
told him I thought
it his duty to go
to - & tell the
real trouble he
believed at bottom
of the tragedy -
entries.summaryText: Visited Dr. Mulligan at home and discussed the real trouble behind a tragedy.

entries.fullText:
Still cant get
back into my
own business -
at evening sister
Mary & self spent
an hour at
Mrs C's - Mr
Barbite was in
- but incapable
of rallying to talk -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about not being able to get back into her own business and spending time with her sister Mary and Mrs C while Mr Barbite was present but unable to talk.

entries.fullText:
a dark & rainy day
Oliver Wendell
Holmes was burried
this day - was 85 years old -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a dark and rainy day and mentions that Oliver Wendell Holmes was buried that day at the age of 85.

entries.fullText:
At Home -
in
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote a short entry about being at home.
Susan B. Anthony did not write an entry on this day.

entries.fullText:
Reached Chicago. 5. P.M.
over the Penn R.R -
Mrs S.E. Gross met me at
Union Depot --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Chicago via the Penn R.R and was met by Mrs S.E. Gross at Union Depot.

entries.fullText: Wea. Fri. Oct. 19, 1894 Ther.

Arrived Kansas City - 8.20
nephew Arthur met me at
Depot for an hour -
arrived - Leavenworth - 12. A.M
found brother D.R. gone - to
Baileyville farm - & Sister
Anna & niece Maude to K.C.
to see Julia Marlowe -(Taber)
How ridiculous for her to
hitch on that no name - to
hers of world wide fame
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Kansas City and met with family members. She also commented on Julia Marlowe's decision to add a no-name to her world-famous name.

entries.fullText: nephew A.A. Mosher wife & son Howard came up to dinner at brother D.R's -
entries.summaryText: Nephew and family visit brother D.R for dinner.

entries.fullText: Wea. TUES. OCT. 23, 1894 Ther.

Wea. WED. OCT. 24, 1894 Ther.
Kansas City
entries.summaryText: Written on October 24, 1894 in Kansas City.

entries.fullText: Ther.
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on October 25, 1894 from Fort Scott.

entries.fullText: Ther.
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on October 26, 1894 from Columbus.

entries.fullText:
Wea. MON. OCT. 29, 1894 Ther.
Laurence
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on October 29, 1894 from Laurence.

entries.fullText:
Wea. TUES. OCT. 30, 1894 Ther.
Enterprise
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on October 30, 1894 from Enterprise.

entries.fullText:
Wea. WED. OCT. 31, 1894 Ther.
Belleville Hotel
entries.summaryText: Entry written on October 31, 1894 at Belleville Hotel.

entries.fullText:
Wea. THUR. NOV. 1, 1894
Burlington
entries.summaryText: Entry written on November 1, 1894 in Burlington.

entries.fullText:
Wea. FRI. NOV. 2, 1894 Ther.
Emporia
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on November 2, 1894 from Emporia.

entries.fullText:
Wea. SAT. NOV. 3, 1894 Ther.
Clay Center
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on November 3, 1894 from Clay Center.

entries.fullText: Wea. Sun. Nov. 4, 1894 Ther.

Topeka -
Metropolitan Hall
- [?] Waters spoke
first perfectly awful
roared like the
bulls of Bashan
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a speech by [?] Waters at Metropolitan Hall in Topeka on November 5, 1894.

entries.fullText:
Election Day -
In Kansas - and
our friends remembered
to forget to vote for -
the Suffrage amendment
while not an enemy
forgot to scratch
his ticket against
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the Suffrage amendment and the forgetfulness of friends and enemies in Kansas on Election Day.

entries.fullText:
Left Topeka at 11 AM
for Beatrice Neb -
for Mrs Colbys Con -
arrived at 6. P.M. Mrs
Lester met & took
me to her next neighbor's
to tea - a nice one - & then
to her house for me to
dress - & thence -without
a breath of rest - drove
back to the Opera House -
a splendid audience
made a historical statement
of the rebuff we
have had in ten states
because of no political
party endorsements --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Beatrice Neb and makes a historical statement about the rebuff of the Suffrage movement in ten states due to lack of political party endorsements.

entries.fullText:
Left Beatrice Neb
8.35 - for
Leavenworth
Dr Harding & Mrs Hull &
husband met me at
Topeka Station -
arrived Leavenworth
at 5.10 - Mrs
Cushing & Mrs Lord called
- all cut down
because amendment
is lost -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Beatrice Neb to Leavenworth and meets with Dr Harding, Mrs Hull, Mrs Cushing, and Mrs Lord.

entries.fullText:
Left Leavenworth
at 4.17 -- & Kansas City
at 6 - on the Chicago
& Alton R.R. for Chicago --
My darling Rachel Foster's
husbands mother - Rosa
Miller Avery died this
afternoon -- aged 64 -
- her son - Cyrus Miller Avery
is her only child --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Leavenworth for Chicago and learns of the death of Rosa Miller Avery, the mother of Rachel Foster's husband.

entries.fullText:
Reached Chicago at
9.30 - A.M - Mrs Chapman
Catt met me at Union
Station where we chatted -
- & then called on Catharine
Waugh McCullough - I went to
Mrs S.E. Gross - & the
first item in Inter Ocean -
was - Rosa Miller Avery dead -
- so after Luncheon - Mrs Gross
sent me out to Edgewater
2653 - Evanston avenue - to
call on Mr Avery - & the
our well beloved son Cyrus
Miller Avery - found dear
Mrs Harkert - there making
the last dress - for the dear
plaintive lady - learned dear
Rachel was on way there -
On return - Mrs Gross
took me to the New
Political Equality League
at Chicago - Celia P. Woolley
Pres - then back to dinner
& a call from darling Mrs
Conley - & Prentiss --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Chicago, attends the New Political Equality League and visits various people and locations.

entries.fullText:
On Pan Handle
Penn. R..R. for Phila
Took 8.20 train at
Chicago & sleeper to
Columbus - Ohio - &
there found I had
better stop from 8. to 11.20
& catch the St Louis
through train with
sleeper to Phila -
dear Mrs Gross is
most open - handed
giving me 2 ten dollar bills
again now - as she did
on my way out to Kansas --
As I go eas to day -
darling Rachel goes West -
Miller rode down with
me yesterday - & poured out
one steady stream of R's
failure to appreciate his mother
& to hold his & her counsel -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Chicago to Philadelphia, stopping in Columbus, and reflects on her interactions with Miller and Mrs. Gross.

entries.fullText:
New York State arrived
Convention - Ithica -
Arrived [Utica]
[Left] Philadelphia
at [9.45 - last] 5 Oclock
this A.M - took breakfast
with nieces Lucy E . and
Anna O. at Miss Shaws
home - 1830 Diamont Street
- Lunch with niece Louise
at 4716 Windsor Avenue -
- with L. called at new
Century Club reception - in
honor of Mary Mapes Dodge -
Mrs Longsheth - President -
then suppered with
dear Miss Thomson
very feeble - & took
sleeper at 9.45 -
for Ithica
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in New York State and attended a convention in Ithica. She had breakfast with her nieces and lunch with her niece Louise. She attended a reception at the new Century Club and had supper with Miss Thomson before taking a sleeper to Ithica.

entries.fullText:
Arrived Ithica at
6.25 - A.M - went to
Clinton Hotel - found
[?] of our women there
- Miss Shaw soon arrived -
made my speech this
evening - & after it
went home with
(the architect)
Mrs Miller - who
has three girls & one son -
to spend the night -
splendid home
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Ithica and stayed at the Clinton Hotel. She made a speech and spent the night at Mrs. Miller's home.

entries.fullText:
In Ithica
all the delegates - by
invitation of Pres Schurman
visited the different
buildings on the Cornell
University Campus -
the Pres. himself taking
us around -
Rev Anna Shaw
spoke this evening - also
the lovely little Mrs Searing of Kingston - a
graduate of Oberlin
Mrs Miller gave a
Luncheon Party - this noon -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Cornell University Campus in Ithica and attends a Luncheon Party.

entries.fullText:
Went to Clinton Hotel
held an Executive
Committee meeting up
to 1. P.M - and
took the train at
4.20 - for Rochester
- arriving 8 - Mary going
to her Club meeting - and
Mrs C.A. Cleveland going
home with me -
to find the girl Sarah
gone - & no one in
House to give us a
supper or anything - I was
simply vexed - still
it was good to get
home - & at last
get settled in my
own bed and [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Rochester and finds her house empty and without supper.

entries.fullText:
- National W.C.T.U. at
Cleveland - Ohio -
--
Slept in my own
bed this night - the 2d one
in succession -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony slept in her own bed in Cleveland, Ohio after attending the National W.C.T.U.

entries.fullText:
Left Rochester 9.45 A.M.
For Cleveland - arriving at
6.25 - P.M - being met by Mrs
Southworths maid -
at station & conducted to her
palatial home - in Street
Cars - 844 - Prospect Street
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony traveled from Rochester to Cleveland and stayed at Mrs. Southworth's home on Prospect Street.

entries.fullText:
In Cleveland -
at Mrs Louise Southworths -
844 - Prospect Street -
Spoke at 5 P.M. in
Union Hall - at a "Gospel
Suffrage Meeting" - !!
entries.summaryText: Spoke at a "Gospel Suffrage Meeting" in Cleveland at Union Hall.

entries.fullText:
In Cleveland - in
Mr Will Southworths lovely
bay window - down stairs
bedroom - large with bath
room & closet-room -
- Held all day Business
meeting of the National -
with - Shaw, Dietrich, Stone
Blackwell, Upton & self - Mrs
Avery & J.H. Hay - about -
- The Lucy Stone Mite
Box Fund - the sad bone
of contention -- but all of
the Com. were for its being a
National Fund - for our disposal
for Kansas work
- except Mrs L.B. who
protested - & declared it
was not for the treasury -
but should go direct to
the Kansas Campaign Com
In evening - the active
Suffrage Women from twelve
States met me - in Mr Southworths
parlor - discussing the relation
of the National to the States --
entries.summaryText: Held a business meeting of the National in Cleveland and discussed the Lucy Stone Mite Box Fund and its use for Kansas work. In the evening, met with active Suffrage Women from twelve states to discuss the relation of the National to the States.

entries.fullText: visited the Ohio State Ex. Com. meeting in the Parlor of the Unity Church - Mrs Everhard presiding - Mrs Casement, Mrs Claypole & others there - Mrs Southworth & Mrs Upton with me - then went
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits the Ohio State Ex. Com. meeting in Cleveland at the Unity Church with several other women.
Susan B. Anthony writes a journal entry in Cleveland on November 21, 1894.

entries.fullText:
Left Cleveland - on the
Boston Car - guest of
Alice Stone Blackwell
Had long talk
with her on her
feelings toward the
National &c and
hope she'll hearafter
not suspect each & all
of some under motive
of not honoring her
mother - for such
distrust seems to have
caused all of her
lack of cordial feeling toward
us all - especially Miss Shaw -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Cleveland and had a long talk with Alice Stone Blackwell about her feelings towards the National &c.

entries.fullText: At home -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at home.

entries.fullText: At home
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at home on November 24, 1894.

entries.fullText:
Worked all day at home
called at evening at Mrs Greenleafs
& took train for New York
at 9.45 -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony worked at home all day on November 25, 1894, visited Mrs. Greenleaf in the evening, and took a train to New York at 9:45 PM.

entries.fullText:
Arrived New York
7.30 this A.M. and
was just in time for
breakfast at Cousin
Samantha Vail Lapham's
- she has with her - cousin
Carrie Vail Ladd - & Miss
Susan Vorse - the latter
as companion, nurse
& housekeeper -
- Called on Mr Robert
Lilley - at Appletons -
72 Fifth Avenue & then
to Ms Stanton's 26 -
West 61st Street to Lunch - &
chat for the afternoon
Then back to cousin
S's - and all went to
cousin Lizzies - John [L??????]
to dinner - he was all ready
to go to one of his clubs - so barely
sat at table - we all spent
the evening - & Cousin Lizzie told
of her new books - read &c
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in New York and had breakfast with Cousin Samantha Vail Lapham, then visited Mr. Robert Lilley and Ms. Stanton, and had lunch and spent the afternoon with Cousin Samantha Vail Lapham and others. In the evening, they went to Cousin Lizzie's and had dinner with John [L??????].

entries.fullText:
In New York
at cousin S.V. Laphams
no 10. East 68th Street -
Immediately after
breakfast - went to
Mrs Stanton's - almost
direct across the Park
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had breakfast at Cousin Samantha Vail Lapham's in New York, then went to visit Mrs. Stanton, who lived almost directly across the Park from Cousin Samantha Vail Lapham's house.

entries.fullText:
In New York
at Cousin S.V. Laphams
& each day going over
& working all day &
lunching with Mrs
Stanton - working
on new article
on 'Woman's Rights" for
the new edition of
Johnson's Cyclopedia
- Vol. 6. of which is now
going to press -
entries.summaryText: Working on a new article on 'Woman's Rights' for the new edition of Johnson's Cyclopedia at Cousin S.V. Laphams and lunching with Mrs Stanton.

entries.fullText:
In New York
Sleeping at
Cousin Samantha's
and working the
days at Mrs
Stantons -
entries.summaryText: Sleeping at Cousin Samantha's and working the days at Mrs Stantons.

entries.fullText:
Wea. SUN. DEC. 2, 1894 Ther.
In New York
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote on December 2, 1894 from New York.

entries.fullText:
Wea. MON. DEC. 3, 1894 Ther.
In New York
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote on December 3, 1894 from New York.

entries.fullText:
Walked across the Park
in twenty minutes this
A.M -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony walked across the Park in twenty minutes.

entries.fullText:
In New York
Cousin S. & Carrie Vail
Ladd with me - dined at
Louis Laphams - 7. East 72d -
Tiffany Apartments - splendid
-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was in New York with Cousin S. and Carrie Vail Ladd. They dined at Louis Laphams and stayed at Tiffany Apartments.

entries.fullText: Walked across the Park - to Mrs Stantons - wrote all day & Cousin S. brought me back at 5.20 Letter from Sister Mary saying Mrs Gross had sent the lovely cloak -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony walked across the Park to Mrs. Stanton's house in New York. She spent the day writing and received a letter from her sister Mary about a lovely cloak sent by Mrs. Gross.

entries.fullText: Mrs Stanton & self - took Luncheon with Dr Mary Putnam Jacobi 110 - West 24th Street - at 2.20 - Josephine Shaw Lowell - Mrs Sanders and Rebecca Sheppard Putnam (Mrs George Putnam) then with us - had a nice time --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had lunch with Mrs. Stanton and Dr. Mary Putnam Jacobi in New York. They were joined by Josephine Shaw Lowell, Mrs. Sanders, and Rebecca Sheppard Putnam and had a nice time.

entries.fullText:
Left New York -
with Miss Vorse - Cousin
Samantha having backed
out - for south
Orange - cousin
Ellen Hoxie Squier -
- Miss Vorse took dinner
& then returned to
New York - - Cousin
Ellen the same lovely
woman - & we had
a good visit -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left New York with Miss Vorse and visited cousin Ellen Hoxie Squier in South Orange.

entries.fullText:
In South Orange
after dinner - cousin
Ellen & self drove
over to Orange to
call on cousin George
Vail & wife - in a
drizzling cold rain -
- on arriving - we found
they had driven over
to call on me - so
we started back - &
met each other about
half way -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited cousin George Vail and his wife in Orange while in South Orange.

entries.fullText:
Left - South Orange
cousin Ellen Hoxie
Squier's - at 9. A.M.
Cousin Lucien & Ellen
going in also - and
went direct to Mrs
Stanton's - & worked
all the day - but
began to feel a cold
coming on -
Found the lovely black
velvet cloak at cousin
Samantha's - all
admired it
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left South Orange and went to Mrs. Stanton's where she worked all day and found a lovely black velvet cloak at cousin Samantha's.

entries.fullText:
In New York
When cousin
Samantha came
for me at 3 P.M,
She brought my
lovely Cape - and I
donned it - & we
called on Mrs Henry
Sanders - 522. 5th ave
& Mrs Lauterbach 2 -
East 78th Street - though
it did rain some ,;,,
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was in New York and visited Mrs Henry Sanders and Mrs Lauterbach with cousin Samantha while wearing her lovely cape.

entries.fullText: A rainy morning - and my cold - no good - so decided not to go to Mrs Stanton's - When fairly seated - a letter from Mrs Lauterbach came - inviting me to go to Opera this evening - I accepted - it was Metropolitan Open Opera House - & the play was Goethe's Faust. - after it - Mr & Mrs L. took me to the Waldorf for a lunch -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives a letter from Mrs. Lauterbach inviting her to the Metropolitan Open Opera House to see Goethe's Faust. After the play, Mr. and Mrs. L. take her to the Waldorf for lunch.

entries.fullText: In New York
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was in New York on December 14, 1894.

entries.fullText:
In New York
at Mrs Stantons all
the day -
Dined at Cousin
Lizzie's (John Laphams)
and she took me
to The Authors [Kn??t]
Leaves" club - at
Sherry's - 'Story Telling'
was the topic - &
some very excellent
stories were told - it
was a 400. gathering -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent December 15, 1894 in New York, visiting Mrs. Stanton's and Cousin Lizzie's, and attending The Authors' Leaves club at Sherry's where the topic was 'Story Telling' and some excellent stories were told in a gathering of 400 people.

entries.fullText: Went to see & hear Robert Collyer - his face - his white hair - his voice - all charming as ever - as cousin Cam[?] said - he was a beautiful picture in the pulpit - he gave me a cordial greeting - at close -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to see and hear Robert Collyer in New York. She describes his appearance and voice and mentions a greeting she received from him.

entries.fullText: Mrs Stanton & self finished up the Article - & I undertook to talk it to Mr Lilley - but a break on track & a car blockade prevented - so went back to cousin Samantha's - and played Desperation - in the evening -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony finished an article with Mrs. Stanton and attempted to talk to Mr. Lilley about it, but was prevented by a break on the track and a car blockade. She then went back to cousin Samantha's and played Desperation in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Called on Mr Lilley
& gave him the
article - completed -
Miss [Gross] Vorse going then
with me - then took
Reading train - & so
got on the through train
& had to go into Phila
so lunched with Lucy E.
at 1820 Diamond st -
& took 4. train back
to Somerton - and
there Rachel & I
had a soul to soul
talk until midnight
& never did I see her
so brave & noble & thus
a woman -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Mr. Lilley and Miss Vorse, takes a train to Philadelphia, has lunch with Lucy E., and has a deep conversation with Rachel until midnight.

entries.fullText:
At Somerton -
Phila - with dear
Rachel Foster Avery
- again we talked
& talked - all the day -
she not even dictating
a single letter -
In the P.M. we both
took a sleep - & then
talked again till 10
Oclock -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day with Rachel Foster Avery, they talk all day and take a nap in the afternoon, and continue talking until 10 pm.

entries.fullText: Mrs. H. J. Uptons little Janey died in Pasadena Cal - this day
entries.summaryText: Mrs. H. J. Uptons little Janey died in Pasadena Cal.

entries.fullText: Left Somerton on the 11.50 train - and lunched with Lucy E. - & Anna O. - then we all went to dear Miss Thomsons to tea - & I spent night there - found Miss T's nephew Edgar [underlined] Thomson there - and learned he had taken money matters in hand - drawing it from J. Edgars estate - & giving to Belle - so much & she accounting to him for every penny - This is a new role - for him to play with the money of Anna or Adeline Thomson -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the day with Lucy E. and Anna O. and then went to Miss Thomson's house where she learned about Edgar Thomson's new role in handling the money of Anna or Adeline Thomson.

entries.fullText: Left Philadelphia - & dear Adeline Thomson for 10.20 train to New York - It looks as if this might be my last sight of her in that frailest of bodies - Belle Parish - & Anna Steele with - the colored women are Aunt Panie - Cook - and Sarah Crawford the nurse - the same that took care of dear Anna, I found Mrs Stanton out - at 1.45 - so called on Louise M. Thomas - 680 - Lexington Avenue - and then on Mrs Gramm's - 33 East 20th street - to [?] or learn when Mrs Sewall was to stop - but got no clue - In evening Mrs Gramm's & Mrs Dietrich called on me at my cousins!.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Philadelphia and went to New York to see Adeline Thomson for the last time. She visited Louise M. Thomas and Mrs Gramm's but could not find out when Mrs Sewall was to stop. In the evening, Mrs Gramm's and Mrs Dietrich called on her at her cousin's.

entries.fullText:
Foremother's Dinner [underlined]
at Yaegers - Cor Madison
Avenue & 59th street - at 12.30 -
- 292 women sat at
the tables - the several
courses & the speeches
lasted until plump 5 Oclock
Mrs Stanton never looked
so beautiful & seren - so
grand & Queenly!! Mrs.
Blake presided well -
May Wright Sewall had excellent
paper on individuality - & cooperation
- Mrs Dietrich did well -
Mrs Chapman Catt did not speak -
May & self dined with Mrs
Stanton - Cousin Lizzie [?]
Lapham came for me - she took
me in her carriage to the dinner -
- Mrs Sewall & cousin Lizzie talked
their Practical Psychology - the
latter almost equaled the former
- on drive home - cousin L. lots
[?] of fame experience that P.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends Foremother's Dinner in New York with several notable women and dines with Mrs. Stanton and Cousin Lizzie.

entries.fullText:
At cousin Semantha's -
called on Dr Mary Putnam
Jacobi - 110 - West 24th street -
to talk over the new [underlined]
work - that of hiring all
sorts of women's clubs
into study clubs - of
Politics & government -
- back to dinner to Cousin S.
her son John there - but
not his wife - at 4 P.M.
Mrs Chapman & Mrs Catt called
& later Mrs Blake & daughter -
& still later - Sen & Anna
Lapham - & her brother.
George & wife
I invited Mrs C.C.
to make the Southern
tour with me - & on
[?] home - Monday 24th I
found telegram that she
would go with me
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony discusses hiring women's clubs into study clubs with Dr. Mary Putnam Jacobi and has several visitors at Cousin Semantha's in New York, including Mrs. Chapman, Mrs. Catt, and Sen Lapham.

entries.fullText:
Left New York on
the Empire State Express
at 8.20 - & reached
Rochester [underlined] - on exact time
3.47 P.M. - Stopping only at
- Albany, Utica & Syracuse en
route - Had been at
cousin Semantha Vail
Laphams - just four weeks
O'nights [underlined] - excepting the two at
cousin Ellen Squier's - and
the two at dear Rachels & the
one at dear - very feeble -
Adeline Thomsons - a
very pleasant visit it has been -
- Cousin Carrie Vail Ladd
came as far as Albany on way
to Fair Haven Vermont - to visit
[with?] sister Lizzies family -
Simeon Allen & two boys - Vail
& George - Harriet May Mills
met me for the five [?]
at Syracuse Depot
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left New York and arrived in Rochester after visiting various relatives and friends in different cities along the way.

entries.fullText:
At Home [underlined]
Sister Mary & self - with
the girl Sarah Baker. The
entire household - sister
M & self had a long talk over
dear Rachel & all our friends
round about when I
have visited the past
month -

We dined with
Dr & Mary Thayer Sanford -
- Mrs L.G. Smith, her
daughter Mrs Fenner
& Mrs - & daughter
there also - a nice
time -

Harriet Taylor Uptons
niece Janey died
in Pasadena California -
yesterday - Dec. [24th] 21st -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent Christmas day at home with her sister and Sarah Baker. They had a long talk about their friends and Rachel. Later, they dined with Dr. and Mary Thayer Sanford, Mrs. L.G. Smith, and others. Harriet Taylor Upton's niece, Janey, passed away in Pasadena, California.

entries.fullText:
At home
went over to Mrs
Greenleaf's - Mrs
Sanford there also -
and worked until
1.30 - to help arrange
the last years financial
report for the printers -
Mr Chapin of Fort
Scott - & his sister of
Westfield Mass - called
in P.M - Maria
Anthony called - so she
talked with Mr. C.
about her money loans
in Kansas - &c In the
evening - Mrs Blackall
with Mrs Frederick Douglass
of Washington D. C. called
- then sister M & I both
wrote letters - & at 10 I
took them to the [?] - &
learned the snow was falling
fast & thick -
